# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: functional-analysis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] In mathematics, more specifically in functional analysis, a **Banach space** (/ˈbɑː.nʌx/, Polish pronunciation: [ˈba.nax]) is a complete normed vector space.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Thus, a Banach space is a vector space with a metric that allows the computation of vector length and distance between vectors and is complete in the sense that a Cauchy sequence of vectors always converges to a well-defined limit that is within the space.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Banach spaces are named after the Polish mathematician Stefan Banach, who introduced this concept and studied it systematically in 1920–1922 along with Hans Hahn and Eduard Helly.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Maurice René Fréchet was the first to use the term "Banach space" and Banach in turn then coined the term "Fréchet space".
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Banach spaces originally grew out of the study of function spaces by Hilbert, Fréchet, and Riesz earlier in the century.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Banach spaces play a central role in functional analysis.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] In other areas of analysis, the spaces under study are often Banach spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] L-semi-inner products are a generalization of inner products, which are what fundamentally distinguish Hilbert spaces from all other Banach spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] This shows that all normed spaces (and hence all Banach spaces) can be considered as being generalizations of (pre-)Hilbert spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The vector space structure allows one to relate the behavior of Cauchy sequences to that of converging series of vectors.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The canonical metric d of a normed space $(X,\|{\cdot }\|)$ induces the usual metric topology $\tau _{d}$ on $X,$ which is referred to as the *canonical* or *norm induced topology*.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Every normed space is automatically assumed to carry this Hausdorff topology, unless indicated otherwise.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] With this topology, every Banach space is a Baire space, although there exist normed spaces that are Baire but not Banach.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The norm $\|{\cdot }\|:X\to \mathbb {R}$ is always a continuous function with respect to the topology that it induces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] In particular, no infinite–dimensional normed space can be locally compact or have the Heine–Borel property.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Consequently, the norm induced topology is completely determined by any neighbourhood basis at the origin.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Additionally, I can always be chosen to be countable if X is a *separable space*, which by definition means that X contains some countable dense subset.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] All finite–dimensional normed spaces are separable Banach spaces and any two Banach spaces of the same finite dimension are linearly homeomorphic.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The Anderson–Kadec theorem states that every infinite–dimensional separable Fréchet space is homeomorphic to the product space ${\textstyle \prod _{i\in \mathbb {N} }\mathbb {R} }$ of countably many copies of $\mathbb {R}$ (this homeomorphism need not be a linear map).
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Thus all infinite–dimensional separable Fréchet spaces are homeomorphic to each other (or said differently, their topology is unique up to a homeomorphism).
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] For example, every open subset U of a Banach space X is canonically a metric Banach manifold modeled on X since the inclusion map $U\to X$ is an open local homeomorphism.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] There is a compact subset S of $\ell ^{2}(\mathbb {N} )$ whose convex hull $\operatorname {co} (S)$ is *not* closed and thus also *not* compact.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] However, like in all Banach spaces, the *closed* convex hull ${\overline {\operatorname {co} }}S$ of this (and every other) compact subset will be compact.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] This norm-induced topology also makes $(X,\tau _{d})$ into what is known as a topological vector space (TVS), which by definition is a vector space endowed with a topology making the operations of addition and scalar multiplication continuous.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] It is emphasized that the TVS $(X,\tau _{d})$ is *only* a vector space together with a certain type of topology; that is to say, when considered as a TVS, it is *not* associated with *any* particular norm or metric (both of which are "forgotten").
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] This Hausdorff TVS $(X,\tau _{d})$ is even locally convex because the set of all open balls centered at the origin forms a neighbourhood basis at the origin consisting of convex balanced open sets.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] This TVS is also *normable*, which by definition refers to any TVS whose topology is induced by some (possibly unknown) norm.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Normable TVSs are characterized by being Hausdorff and having a bounded convex neighborhood of the origin.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] All Banach spaces are barrelled spaces, which means that every barrel is neighborhood of the origin (all closed balls centered at the origin are barrels, for example) and guarantees that the Banach–Steinhaus theorem holds.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] See this footnote for an example of a continuous norm on a Banach space that is *not* equivalent to that Banach space's given norm.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] All norms on a finite-dimensional vector space are equivalent and every finite-dimensional normed space is a Banach space.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] If D is *not* translation invariant, then it may be possible for $(X,\|{\cdot }\|)$ to be a Banach space but for $(X,D)$ to *not* be a complete metric space (see this footnote for an example).
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] In contrast, a theorem of Klee, which also applies to all metrizable topological vector spaces, implies that if there exists *any* complete metric D on X that induces the norm topology $\tau$ on $X,$ then $(X,\|{\cdot }\|)$ is a Banach space.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] A Fréchet space is a locally convex topological vector space whose topology is induced by some translation-invariant complete metric.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Every Banach space is a Fréchet space but not conversely; indeed, there even exist Fréchet spaces on which no norm is a continuous function (such as the space of real sequences ${\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{\mathbb {N} }=\prod _{i\in \mathbb {N} }\mathbb {R} }$ with the product topology).
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] However, the topology of every Fréchet space is induced by some countable family of real-valued (necessarily continuous) maps called seminorms, which are generalizations of norms.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] It is even possible for a Fréchet space to have a topology that is induced by a countable family of *norms* (such norms would necessarily be continuous) but to not be a Banach/normable space because its topology can not be defined by any *single* norm.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] An example of such a space is the Fréchet space $C^{\infty }(K),$ whose definition can be found in the article on spaces of test functions and distributions.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] There is another notion of completeness besides metric completeness and that is the notion of a complete topological vector space (TVS) or TVS-completeness, which uses the theory of uniform spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Moreover, a normed space is a Banach space (that is, its norm-induced metric is complete) if and only if it is complete as a topological vector space.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] If X is a metrizable locally convex TVS, then X is normable if and only if $X'_{b}$ is a Fréchet–Urysohn space.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] This shows that in the category of locally convex TVSs, Banach spaces are exactly those complete spaces that are both metrizable and have metrizable strong dual spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Every normed space can be isometrically embedded onto a dense vector subspace of a Banach space, where this Banach space is called a *completion* of the normed space.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] This Hausdorff completion is unique up to isometric isomorphism.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] If X and Y are normed spaces over the same ground field $\mathbb {K} ,$ the set of all continuous $\mathbb {K}$ -linear maps $T:X\to Y$ is denoted by $B(X,Y).$ In infinite-dimensional spaces, not all linear maps are continuous.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] For Y a Banach space, the space $B(X,Y)$ is a Banach space with respect to this norm.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] In categorical contexts, it is sometimes convenient to restrict the function space between two Banach spaces to only the short maps; in that case the space $B(X,Y)$ reappears as a natural bifunctor.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] If X is a Banach space, the space $B(X)=B(X,X)$ forms a unital Banach algebra; the multiplication operation is given by the composition of linear maps.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] If X and Y are normed spaces, they are **isomorphic normed spaces** if there exists a linear bijection $T:X\to Y$ such that T and its inverse $T^{-1}$ are continuous.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] If one of the two spaces X or Y is complete (or reflexive, separable, etc.) then so is the other space.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Two normed spaces X and Y are *isometrically isomorphic* if in addition, T is an isometry, that is, $\|T(x)\|=\|x\|$ for every x in $X.$ The Banach–Mazur distance $d(X,Y)$ between two isomorphic but not isometric spaces X and Y gives a measure of how much the two spaces X and Y differ.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Every continuous linear operator is a bounded linear operator and if dealing only with normed spaces then the converse is also true.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] That is, a linear operator between two normed spaces is bounded if and only if it is a continuous function.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] So in particular, because the scalar field (which is $\mathbb {R}$ or $\mathbb {C}$ ) is a normed space, a linear functional on a normed space is a bounded linear functional if and only if it is a continuous linear functional.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] This allows for continuity-related results (like those below) to be applied to Banach spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Although boundedness is the same as continuity for linear maps between normed spaces, the term "bounded" is more commonly used when dealing primarily with Banach spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The Cartesian product $X\times Y$ of two normed spaces is not canonically equipped with a norm.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] However, several equivalent norms are commonly used, such as $\|(x,y)\|_{1}=\|x\|+\|y\|,\qquad \|(x,y)\|_{\infty }=\max(\|x\|,\|y\|)$ which correspond (respectively) to the coproduct and product in the category of Banach spaces and short maps (discussed above).
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] For finite (co)products, these norms give rise to isomorphic normed spaces, and the product $X\times Y$ (or the direct sum $X\oplus Y$ ) is complete if and only if the two factors are complete.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The quotient $X/M$ is a Banach space when X is complete.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The quotient map from X onto $X/M,$ sending $x\in X$ to its class $x+M,$ is linear, onto, and of norm $1,$ except when $M=X,$ in which case the quotient is the null space.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The mapping $T_{1}$ is a linear bijection from $X/\ker T$ onto the range $T(X),$ whose inverse need not be bounded.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Any Hilbert space serves as an example of a Banach space.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] For example, the space $L^{2}$ is a Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The Hardy spaces, the Sobolev spaces are examples of Banach spaces that are related to $L^{p}$ spaces and have additional structure.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] They are important in different branches of analysis, Harmonic analysis and Partial differential equations among others.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] A *Banach algebra* is a Banach space A over $\mathbb {K} =\mathbb {R}$ or $\mathbb {C} ,$ together with a structure of algebra over $\mathbb {K}$ , such that the product map $A\times A\ni (a,b)\mapsto ab\in A$ is continuous.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] If X is a normed space and $\mathbb {K}$ the underlying field (either the reals or the complex numbers), the *continuous dual space* is the space of continuous linear maps from X into $\mathbb {K} ,$ or *continuous linear functionals*.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The notation for the continuous dual is $X'=B(X,\mathbb {K} )$ in this article.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Since $\mathbb {K}$ is a Banach space (using the absolute value as norm), the dual $X'$ is a Banach space, for every normed space $X.$ The Dixmier–Ng theorem characterizes the dual spaces of Banach spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The main tool for proving the existence of continuous linear functionals is the Hahn–Banach theorem.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] In particular, every continuous linear functional on a subspace of a normed space can be continuously extended to the whole space, without increasing the norm of the functional.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The Hahn–Banach separation theorem states that two disjoint non-empty convex sets in a real Banach space, one of them open, can be separated by a closed affine hyperplane.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The open convex set lies strictly on one side of the hyperplane, the second convex set lies on the other side but may touch the hyperplane.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] A subset S in a Banach space X is *total* if the linear span of S is dense in $X.$ The subset S is total in X if and only if the only continuous linear functional that vanishes on S is the $\mathbf {0}$ functional: this equivalence follows from the Hahn–Banach theorem.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The orthogonal $M^{\bot }$ is a closed linear subspace of the dual.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The *weak topology* on a Banach space X is the coarsest topology on X for which all elements $x'$ in the continuous dual space $X'$ are continuous.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The norm topology is therefore finer than the weak topology.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] It follows from the Hahn–Banach separation theorem that the weak topology is Hausdorff, and that a norm-closed convex subset of a Banach space is also weakly closed.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] If X is infinite-dimensional, there exist linear maps which are not continuous.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The space $X^{*}$ of all linear maps from X to the underlying field $\mathbb {K}$ (this space $X^{*}$ is called the algebraic dual space, to distinguish it from $X'$ also induces a topology on X which is finer than the weak topology, and much less used in functional analysis.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] On a dual space $X',$ there is a topology weaker than the weak topology of $X',$ called the *weak* topology*.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] It is the coarsest topology on $X'$ for which all evaluation maps $x'\in X'\mapsto x'(x),$ where x ranges over $X,$ are continuous.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Its importance comes from the Banach–Alaoglu theorem.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The Banach–Alaoglu theorem can be proved using Tychonoff's theorem about infinite products of compact Hausdorff spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] When X is separable, the unit ball $B'$ of the dual is a metrizable compact in the weak* topology.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The dual of $\ell ^{1}$ is isometrically isomorphic to $\ell ^{\infty }$ .
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] When K is a compact Hausdorff topological space, the dual $M(K)$ of $C(K)$ is the space of Radon measures in the sense of Bourbaki.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] More generally, by the Gelfand–Mazur theorem, the maximal ideals of a unital commutative Banach algebra can be identified with its characters—not merely as sets but as topological spaces: the former with the hull-kernel topology and the latter with the w*-topology.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Not every unital commutative Banach algebra is of the form $C(K)$ for some compact Hausdorff space $K.$ However, this statement holds if one places $C(K)$ in the smaller category of commutative C*-algebras.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Gelfand's representation theorem for commutative C*-algebras states that every commutative unital *C**-algebra A is isometrically isomorphic to a $C(K)$ space.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The Hausdorff compact space K here is again the maximal ideal space, also called the spectrum of A in the C*-algebra context.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] This defines $F_{X}(x)$ as a continuous linear functional on $X',$ that is, an element of $X''.$ The map $F_{X}\colon x\to F_{X}(x)$ is a linear map from X to $X''.$ As a consequence of the existence of a norming functional f for every $x\in X,$ this map $F_{X}$ is isometric, thus injective.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] For example, the dual of $X=c_{0}$ is identified with $\ell ^{1},$ and the dual of $\ell ^{1}$ is identified with $\ell ^{\infty },$ the space of bounded scalar sequences.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Under these identifications, $F_{X}$ is the inclusion map from $c_{0}$ to $\ell ^{\infty }.$ It is indeed isometric, but not onto.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] If $F_{X}$ is surjective, then the normed space X is called *reflexive* (see below).
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Being the dual of a normed space, the bidual $X''$ is complete, therefore, every reflexive normed space is a Banach space.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Using the isometric embedding $F_{X},$ it is customary to consider a normed space X as a subset of its bidual.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] When X is a Banach space, it is viewed as a closed linear subspace of $X''.$ If X is not reflexive, the unit ball of X is a proper subset of the unit ball of $X''.$ The Goldstine theorem states that the unit ball of a normed space is weakly*-dense in the unit ball of the bidual.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The net may be replaced by a weakly*-convergent sequence when the dual $X'$ is separable.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] On the other hand, elements of the bidual of $\ell ^{1}$ that are not in $\ell ^{1}$ cannot be weak*-limit of *sequences* in $\ell ^{1},$ since $\ell ^{1}$ is weakly sequentially complete.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Here are the main general results about Banach spaces that go back to the time of Banach's book (Banach (1932)) and are related to the Baire category theorem.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] According to this theorem, a complete metric space (such as a Banach space, a Fréchet space or an F-space) cannot be equal to a union of countably many closed subsets with empty interiors.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Therefore, a Banach space cannot be the union of countably many closed subspaces, unless it is already equal to one of them; a Banach space with a countable Hamel basis is finite-dimensional.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The Banach–Steinhaus theorem is not limited to Banach spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] This result is a direct consequence of the preceding *Banach isomorphism theorem* and of the canonical factorization of bounded linear maps.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The normed space X is called *reflexive* when the natural map ${\begin{cases}F_{X}:X\to X''\\F_{X}(x)(f)=f(x)&{\text{ for all }}x\in X,{\text{ and for all }}f\in X'\end{cases}}$ is surjective.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Reflexive normed spaces are Banach spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] This is a consequence of the Hahn–Banach theorem.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Further, by the open mapping theorem, if there is a bounded linear operator from the Banach space X onto the Banach space $Y,$ then Y is reflexive.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Indeed, if the dual $Y'$ of a Banach space Y is separable, then Y is separable.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] If X is reflexive and separable, then the dual of $X'$ is separable, so $X'$ is separable.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The $L^{p}$ spaces are reflexive when $1<p<\infty .$ More generally, uniformly convex spaces are reflexive, by the Milman–Pettis theorem.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] In these examples of non-reflexive spaces $X,$ the bidual $X''$ is "much larger" than $X.$ Namely, under the natural isometric embedding of X into $X''$ given by the Hahn–Banach theorem, the quotient $X''/X$ is infinite-dimensional, and even nonseparable.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] James has constructed an example of a non-reflexive space, usually called "*the James space*" and denoted by $J,$ such that the quotient $J''/J$ is one-dimensional.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Furthermore, this space J is isometrically isomorphic to its bidual.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] When X is reflexive, it follows that all closed and bounded convex subsets of X are weakly compact.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] In a Hilbert space $H,$ the weak compactness of the unit ball is very often used in the following way: every bounded sequence in H has weakly convergent subsequences.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Weak compactness of the unit ball provides a tool for finding solutions in reflexive spaces to certain optimization problems.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] As a special case of the preceding result, when X is a reflexive space over $\mathbb {R} ,$ every continuous linear functional f in $X'$ attains its maximum $\|f\|$ on the unit ball of $X.$ The following theorem of Robert C.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The theorem can be extended to give a characterization of weakly compact convex sets.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] On every non-reflexive Banach space $X,$ there exist continuous linear functionals that are not *norm-attaining*.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] When the sequence $\{x_{n}\}$ in X is a weakly Cauchy sequence, the limit L above defines a bounded linear functional on the dual $X',$ that is, an element L of the bidual of $X,$ and L is the limit of $\{x_{n}\}$ in the weak*-topology of the bidual.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The Banach space X is *weakly sequentially complete* if every weakly Cauchy sequence is weakly convergent in $X.$ It follows from the preceding discussion that reflexive spaces are weakly sequentially complete.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] An orthonormal sequence in a Hilbert space is a simple example of a weakly convergent sequence, with limit equal to the $\mathbf {0}$ vector.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The unit vector basis of $\ell ^{1}$ is not weakly Cauchy.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Weakly Cauchy sequences in $\ell ^{1}$ are weakly convergent, since $L^{1}$ -spaces are weakly sequentially complete.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Actually, weakly convergent sequences in $\ell ^{1}$ are norm convergent.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] This means that $\ell ^{1}$ satisfies Schur's property.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Weakly Cauchy sequences and the $\ell ^{1}$ basis are the opposite cases of the dichotomy established in the following deep result of Haskell P.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] A complement to this result is due to Odell and Rosenthal (1975).
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] When X is separable, the unit ball of the dual is weak*-compact by the Banach–Alaoglu theorem and metrizable for the weak* topology, hence every bounded sequence in the dual has weakly* convergent subsequences.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] This applies to separable reflexive spaces, but more is true in this case, as stated below.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] The weak topology of a Banach space X is metrizable if and only if X is finite-dimensional.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] If the dual $X'$ is separable, the weak topology of the unit ball of X is metrizable.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] This applies in particular to separable reflexive Banach spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] Although the weak topology of the unit ball is not metrizable in general, one can characterize weak compactness using sequences.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] A Banach space X is reflexive if and only if each bounded sequence in X has a weakly convergent subsequence.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] A weakly compact subset A in $\ell ^{1}$ is norm-compact.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p01] A way to classify Banach spaces is through the probabilistic notion of type and cotype, these two measure how far a Banach space is from a Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] Banach spaces with a Schauder basis are necessarily separable, because the countable set of finite linear combinations with rational coefficients (say) is dense.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] It follows from the Banach–Steinhaus theorem that the linear mappings $\{P_{n}\}$ are uniformly bounded by some constant $C.$ Let $\{e_{n}^{*}\}$ denote the coordinate functionals which assign to every x in X the coordinate $x_{n}$ of x in the above expansion.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] They are called *biorthogonal functionals*.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] Most classical separable spaces have explicit bases.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] Since every vector x in a Banach space X with a basis is the limit of $P_{n}(x),$ with $P_{n}$ of finite rank and uniformly bounded, the space X satisfies the bounded approximation property.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] The first example by Enflo of a space failing the approximation property was at the same time the first example of a separable Banach space without a Schauder basis.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] James characterized reflexivity in Banach spaces with a basis: the space X with a Schauder basis is reflexive if and only if the basis is both shrinking and boundedly complete.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] Let X and Y be two $\mathbb {K}$ -vector spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] The image under T of a couple $(x,y)$ in $X\times Y$ is denoted by $x\otimes y,$ and called a *simple tensor*.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] Every element z in $X\otimes Y$ is a finite sum of such simple tensors.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] There are various norms that can be placed on the tensor product of the underlying vector spaces, amongst others the projective cross norm and injective cross norm introduced by A.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] In general, the tensor product of complete spaces is not complete again.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] The tensor product $X'{\widehat {\otimes }}_{\varepsilon }X$ is identified isometrically with the closure in $B(X)$ of the set of finite rank operators.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] For every Banach space $Y,$ there is a natural norm 1 linear map $Y{\widehat {\otimes }}_{\pi }X\to Y{\widehat {\otimes }}_{\varepsilon }X$ obtained by extending the identity map of the algebraic tensor product.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] Grothendieck conjectured that $X{\widehat {\otimes }}_{\pi }Y$ and $X{\widehat {\otimes }}_{\varepsilon }Y$ must be different whenever X and Y are infinite-dimensional Banach spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] This was disproved by Gilles Pisier in 1983.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] Pisier constructed an infinite-dimensional Banach space X such that $X{\widehat {\otimes }}_{\pi }X$ and $X{\widehat {\otimes }}_{\varepsilon }X$ are equal.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] Furthermore, just as Enflo's example, this space X is a "hand-made" space that fails to have the approximation property.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] On the other hand, Szankowski proved that the classical space $B(\ell ^{2})$ does not have the approximation property.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] It follows, for example, that the Lebesgue space $L^{p}([0,1])$ is a Hilbert space only when $p=2.$ If this identity is satisfied, the associated inner product is given by the polarization identity.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] Several characterizations of spaces isomorphic (rather than isometric) to Hilbert spaces are available.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] Here, $\operatorname {Ave} _{\pm }$ denotes the average over the $2^{n}$ possible choices of signs $\pm 1.$ In the same article, Kwapień proved that the validity of a Banach-valued Parseval's theorem for the Fourier transform characterizes Banach spaces isomorphic to Hilbert spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] Lindenstrauss and Tzafriri proved that a Banach space in which every closed linear subspace is complemented (that is, is the range of a bounded linear projection) is isomorphic to a Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] The proof rests upon Dvoretzky's theorem about Euclidean sections of high-dimensional centrally symmetric convex bodies.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] In other words, Dvoretzky's theorem states that for every integer $n,$ any finite-dimensional normed space, with dimension sufficiently large compared to $n,$ contains subspaces nearly isometric to the n -dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] The next result gives the solution of the so-called *homogeneous space problem*.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] An infinite-dimensional Banach space X is said to be *homogeneous* if it is isomorphic to all its infinite-dimensional closed subspaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] A Banach space isomorphic to $\ell ^{2}$ is homogeneous, and Banach asked for the converse.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] An infinite-dimensional Banach space is *hereditarily indecomposable* when no subspace of it can be isomorphic to the direct sum of two infinite-dimensional Banach spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] The Gowers dichotomy theorem asserts that every infinite-dimensional Banach space X contains, either a subspace Y with unconditional basis, or a hereditarily indecomposable subspace $Z,$ and in particular, Z is not isomorphic to its closed hyperplanes.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] If X is homogeneous, it must therefore have an unconditional basis.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] If $T:X\to Y$ is an isometry from the Banach space X onto the Banach space Y (where both X and Y are vector spaces over $\mathbb {R}$ ), then the Mazur–Ulam theorem states that T must be an affine transformation.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] In particular, if $T(0_{X})=0_{Y},$ this is T maps the zero of X to the zero of $Y,$ then T must be linear.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] This result implies that the metric in Banach spaces, and more generally in normed spaces, completely captures their linear structure.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] Finite dimensional Banach spaces are homeomorphic as topological spaces, if and only if they have the same dimension as real vector spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] Anderson–Kadec theorem (1965–66) proves that any two infinite-dimensional separable Banach spaces are homeomorphic as topological spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] Kadec's theorem was extended by Torunczyk, who proved that any two Banach spaces are homeomorphic if and only if they have the same density character, the minimum cardinality of a dense subset.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] When two compact Hausdorff spaces $K_{1}$ and $K_{2}$ are homeomorphic, the Banach spaces $C(K_{1})$ and $C(K_{2})$ are isometric.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] Conversely, when $K_{1}$ is not homeomorphic to $K_{2},$ the (multiplicative) Banach–Mazur distance between $C(K_{1})$ and $C(K_{2})$ must be greater than or equal to $2,$ see above the results by Amir and Cambern.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] The situation is different for countably infinite compact Hausdorff spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] Every countably infinite compact K is homeomorphic to some closed interval of ordinal numbers $\langle 1,\alpha \rangle =\{\gamma \mid 1\leq \gamma \leq \alpha \}$ equipped with the order topology, where $\alpha$ is a countably infinite ordinal.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] The Banach space $C(K)$ is then isometric to *C*(⟨1, *α*⟩).
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] When $\alpha ,\beta$ are two countably infinite ordinals, and assuming $\alpha \leq \beta ,$ the spaces *C*(⟨1, *α*⟩) and *C*(⟨1, *β*⟩) are isomorphic if and only if *β* < *αω*.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] For example, the Banach spaces $C(\langle 1,\omega \rangle ),\ C(\langle 1,\omega ^{\omega }\rangle ),\ C(\langle 1,\omega ^{\omega ^{2}}\rangle ),\ C(\langle 1,\omega ^{\omega ^{3}}\rangle ),\cdots ,C(\langle 1,\omega ^{\omega ^{\omega }}\rangle ),\cdots$ are mutually non-isomorphic.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] Several concepts of a derivative may be defined on a Banach space.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] See the articles on the Fréchet derivative and the Gateaux derivative for details.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] The Fréchet derivative allows for an extension of the concept of a total derivative to Banach spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] The Gateaux derivative allows for an extension of a directional derivative to locally convex topological vector spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] Fréchet differentiability is a stronger condition than Gateaux differentiability.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] The quasi-derivative is another generalization of directional derivative that implies a stronger condition than Gateaux differentiability, but a weaker condition than Fréchet differentiability.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] Several important spaces in functional analysis, for instance the space of all infinitely often differentiable functions $\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} ,$ or the space of all distributions on $\mathbb {R} ,$ are complete but are not normed vector spaces and hence not Banach spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/banach-space-p02] In Fréchet spaces one still has a complete metric, while LF-spaces are complete uniform vector spaces arising as limits of Fréchet spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] In mathematics, any vector space *V* has a corresponding **dual vector space** (or just **dual space** for short) consisting of all linear forms on *$V,$* together with the vector space structure of pointwise addition and scalar multiplication by constants.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] The dual space as defined above is defined for all vector spaces, and to avoid ambiguity may also be called the *algebraic dual space*.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] When defined for a topological vector space, there is a subspace of the dual space, corresponding to continuous linear functionals, called the **continuous dual space**.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Dual vector spaces find application in many branches of mathematics that use vector spaces, such as in tensor analysis with finite-dimensional vector spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] When applied to vector spaces of functions (which are typically infinite-dimensional), dual spaces are used to describe measures, distributions, and Hilbert spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Consequently, the dual space is an important concept in functional analysis.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Early terms for *dual* include *polarer Raum* [Hahn 1927], *espace conjugué*, *adjoint space* [Alaoglu 1940], and *transponierter Raum* [Schauder 1930] and [Banach 1932].
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] The term *dual* is due to Bourbaki 1938.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Given any vector space V over a field F , the **(algebraic) dual space** $V^{*}$ (alternatively denoted by $V^{\lor }$ or $V'$ ) is defined as the set of all linear maps *$\varphi :V\to F$* (linear functionals).
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Since linear maps are vector space homomorphisms, the dual space may be denoted $\hom(V,F)$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] is an element of $(\mathbb {R} ^{2})^{*}$ , since it is $\mathbb {R}$ -linear and maps vectors in $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ to elements of $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Elements of the algebraic dual space $V^{*}$ are sometimes called **covectors**, **one-forms**, or **linear forms**.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] The pairing of a functional *$\varphi$* in the dual space $V^{*}$ and an element *x* of *V* is sometimes denoted by a bracket: *$\varphi (x)=[x,\varphi ]$* or *$\varphi (x)=\langle x,\varphi \rangle$*.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] This pairing defines a nondegenerate bilinear mapping $\langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle :V\times V^{*}\to F$ called the natural pairing.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Given a vector space V and a basis E on that space, one can define a linearly independent set in $V^{*}$ called the dual set.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Each vector in E corresponds to a unique vector in the dual set.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] This correspondence yields an injection $V\to V^{*}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] If V is finite-dimensional, the dual set is a basis, called the dual basis, and the injection $V\to V^{*}$ is an isomorphism.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] In particular, letting in turn each one of those coefficients be equal to one and the other coefficients zero, gives the system of equations $\mathbf {e} ^{i}(\mathbf {e} _{j})=\delta _{j}^{i}$ where $\delta _{j}^{i}$ is the Kronecker delta symbol.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] This property is referred to as the *bi-orthogonality property*.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] The basis vectors are not orthogonal to each other.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] even when the basis vectors are not orthogonal to each other.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Strictly speaking, the above statement only makes sense once the inner product $\langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle$ and the corresponding duality pairing are introduced, as described below in *§ Bilinear products and dual spaces*.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] In particular, $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ can be interpreted as the space of columns of n real numbers, its dual space is typically written as the space of *rows* of n real numbers.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Such a row acts on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ as a linear functional by ordinary matrix multiplication.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] This is because a functional maps every n -vector x into a real number y .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Then, seeing this functional as a matrix M , and x as an $n\times 1$ matrix, and y a $1\times 1$ matrix (trivially, a real number) respectively, if $Mx=y$ then, by dimension reasons, M must be a $1\times n$ matrix; that is, M must be a row vector.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] If V consists of the space of geometrical vectors in the plane, then the level curves of an element of $V^{*}$ form a family of parallel lines in V , because the range is 1-dimensional, so that every point in the range is a multiple of any one nonzero element.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] So an element of $V^{*}$ can be intuitively thought of as a particular family of parallel lines covering the plane.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] To compute the value of a functional on a given vector, it suffices to determine which of the lines the vector lies on.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Informally, this "counts" how many lines the vector crosses.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] More generally, if V is a vector space of any dimension, then the level sets of a linear functional in $V^{*}$ are parallel hyperplanes in V , and the action of a linear functional on a vector can be visualized in terms of these hyperplanes.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] If V is not finite-dimensional but has a basis $\mathbf {e} _{\alpha }$ indexed by an infinite set A , then the same construction as in the finite-dimensional case yields linearly independent elements $\mathbf {e} ^{\alpha }$ ( $\alpha \in A$ ) of the dual space, but they will not form a basis.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] For instance, consider the space $\mathbb {R} ^{\infty }$ , whose elements are those sequences of real numbers that contain only finitely many non-zero entries, which has a basis indexed by the natural numbers $\mathbb {N}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] For $i\in \mathbb {N}$ , $\mathbf {e} _{i}$ is the sequence consisting of all zeroes except in the i -th position, which is 1.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] which is a finite sum because there are only finitely many nonzero $x_{n}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] The dimension of $\mathbb {R} ^{\infty }$ is countably infinite, whereas $\mathbb {R} ^{\mathbb {N} }$ does not have a countable basis.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] in V (the sum is finite by the assumption on f , and any $v\in V$ may be written uniquely in this way by the definition of the basis).
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Again, the sum is finite because $f_{\alpha }$ is nonzero for only finitely many $\alpha$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] If a vector space is not finite-dimensional, then its (algebraic) dual space is *always* of larger dimension (as a cardinal number) than the original vector space.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] This is in contrast to the case of the continuous dual space, discussed below, which may be isomorphic to the original vector space even if the latter is infinite-dimensional.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] The proof of this inequality between dimensions results from the following.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] If V is an infinite-dimensional F -vector space, the arithmetical properties of cardinal numbers implies that $\mathrm {dim} (V)=|A|<|F|^{|A|}=|V^{\ast }|=\mathrm {max} (|\mathrm {dim} (V^{\ast })|,|F|),$ where cardinalities are denoted as absolute values.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] For proving that $\mathrm {dim} (V)<\mathrm {dim} (V^{*}),$ it suffices to prove that $|F|\leq |\mathrm {dim} (V^{\ast })|,$ which can be done with an argument similar to Cantor's diagonal argument.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] The exact dimension of the dual is given by the Erdős–Kaplansky theorem.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] If V is finite-dimensional, then V is isomorphic to $V^{*}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] But there is in general no natural isomorphism between these two spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] where the right hand side is defined as the functional on V taking each $w\in V$ to $\langle v,w\rangle$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] If the bilinear form is nondegenerate, then this is an isomorphism onto a subspace of $V^{*}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] If V is finite-dimensional, then this is an isomorphism onto all of $V^{*}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Thus there is a one-to-one correspondence between isomorphisms of V to a subspace of (resp., all of) $V^{*}$ and nondegenerate bilinear forms on V .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] If the vector space V is over the complex field, then sometimes it is more natural to consider sesquilinear forms instead of bilinear forms.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] There is a natural homomorphism $\Psi$ from V into the double dual $V^{**}=\hom(V^{*},F)$ , defined by $(\Psi (v))(\varphi )=\varphi (v)$ for all $v\in V,\varphi \in V^{*}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] In other words, if $\mathrm {ev} _{v}:V^{*}\to F$ is the evaluation map defined by $\varphi \mapsto \varphi (v)$ , then $\Psi :V\to V^{**}$ is defined as the map $v\mapsto \mathrm {ev} _{v}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] This map $\Psi$ is always injective; and it is always an isomorphism if V is finite-dimensional.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Indeed, the isomorphism of a finite-dimensional vector space with its double dual is an archetypal example of a natural isomorphism.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Infinite-dimensional Hilbert spaces are not isomorphic to their algebraic double duals, but instead to their continuous double duals.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] The resulting functional *$f^{*}(\varphi )$* in *$V^{*}$* is called the *pullback* of *$\varphi$* along *f*.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] The following identity holds for all *$\varphi \in W^{*}$* and *$v\in V$*: $[f^{*}(\varphi ),\,v]=[\varphi ,\,f(v)],$ where the bracket $[\cdot ,\cdot ]$ on the left is the natural pairing of V with its dual space, and that on the right is the natural pairing of W with its dual.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] This identity characterizes the transpose, and is formally similar to the definition of the adjoint.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] The assignment $f\mapsto f^{*}$ produces an injective linear map between the space of linear operators from V to W and the space of linear operators from $W^{*}$ to $V^{*}$ ; this homomorphism is an isomorphism if and only if W is finite-dimensional.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] If $V=W$ then the space of linear maps is actually an algebra under composition of maps, and the assignment is then an antihomomorphism of algebras, meaning that ${(fg)}^{*}=g^{*}f^{*}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] In the language of category theory, taking the dual of vector spaces and the transpose of linear maps is therefore a contravariant functor from the category of vector spaces over F to itself.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] It is possible to identify $f^{**}$ with f using the natural injection into the double dual.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] If the linear map f is represented by the matrix A with respect to two bases of V and W , then $f^{*}$ is represented by the transpose matrix $A^{T}$ with respect to the dual bases of $W^{*}$ and $V^{*}$ , hence the name.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Alternatively, as f is represented by A acting on the left on column vectors, $f^{*}$ is represented by the same matrix acting on the right on row vectors.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] These points of view are related by the canonical inner product on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , which identifies the space of column vectors with the dual space of row vectors.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] The **annihilator** of S in $V^{*}$ , denoted here $S^{0}$ , is the collection of linear functionals $f\in V^{*}$ such that $[f,s]=0$ for all $s\in S$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] That is, $S^{0}$ consists of all linear functionals $f:V\to F$ such that the restriction to S vanishes: $f|_{S}=0$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Within finite dimensional vector spaces, the annihilator is dual to (isomorphic to) the orthogonal complement.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] The annihilator of a subset is itself a vector space.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] The annihilator of the zero vector is the whole dual space: $\{0\}^{0}=V^{*}$ , and the annihilator of the whole space is just the zero covector: $V^{0}=\{0\}\subseteq V^{*}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] If V is finite-dimensional and W is a vector subspace, then $W^{00}=W$ after identifying W with its image in the second dual space under the double duality isomorphism $V\approx V^{**}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] In particular, forming the annihilator is a Galois connection on the lattice of subsets of a finite-dimensional vector space.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] If W is a subspace of V then the quotient space $V/W$ is a vector space in its own right, and so has a dual.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] By the first isomorphism theorem, a functional $f:V\to F$ factors through $V/W$ if and only if W is in the kernel of f .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] As a particular consequence, if V is a direct sum of two subspaces A and B , then $V^{*}$ is a direct sum of $A^{0}$ and $B^{0}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] The dual space is analogous to a "negative"-dimensional space.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Most simply, since a vector $v\in V$ can be paired with a covector $\varphi \in V^{*}$ by the natural pairing $\langle x,\varphi \rangle :=\varphi (x)\in F$ to obtain a scalar, a covector can "cancel" the dimension of a vector, similar to reducing a fraction.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Thus while the direct sum $V\oplus V^{*}$ is a $2n$ -dimensional space (if V is n -dimensional), $V^{*}$ behaves as an $-n$ -dimensional space, in the sense that its dimensions can be canceled against the dimensions of V .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] This is formalized by tensor contraction.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] This arises in physics via dimensional analysis, where the dual space has inverse units.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Under the natural pairing, these units cancel, and the resulting scalar value is dimensionless, as expected.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] For example, in (continuous) Fourier analysis, or more broadly time–frequency analysis: given a one-dimensional vector space with a unit of time t , the dual space has units of frequency: occurrences *per* unit of time (units of $1/t$ ).
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] For example, if time is measured in seconds, the corresponding dual unit is the inverse second: over the course of 3 seconds, an event that occurs 2 times per second occurs a total of 6 times, corresponding to $3s\cdot 2s^{-1}=6$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Similarly, if the primal space measures length, the dual space measures inverse length.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] When dealing with topological vector spaces, the continuous linear functionals from the space into the base field $\mathbb {F} =\mathbb {C}$ (or $\mathbb {R}$ ) are particularly important.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] This gives rise to the notion of the "continuous dual space" or "topological dual" which is a linear subspace of the algebraic dual space $V^{*}$ , denoted by $V'$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] For any *finite-dimensional* normed vector space or topological vector space, such as Euclidean *n-*space, the continuous dual and the algebraic dual coincide.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] This is however false for any infinite-dimensional normed space, as shown by the example of discontinuous linear maps.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Nevertheless, in the theory of topological vector spaces the terms "continuous dual space" and "topological dual space" are often replaced by "dual space".
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] For a topological vector space V its *continuous dual space*, or *topological dual space*, or just *dual space* (in the sense of the theory of topological vector spaces) $V'$ is defined as the space of all continuous linear functionals $\varphi :V\to {\mathbb {F} }$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] If X is a Hausdorff topological vector space (TVS), then the continuous dual space of X is identical to the continuous dual space of the completion of X .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] There is a standard construction for introducing a topology on the continuous dual $V'$ of a topological vector space V .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Fix a collection ${\mathcal {A}}$ of bounded subsets of V .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Here are the three most important special cases.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] In a similar manner, the continuous dual of $\ell ^{1}$ is naturally identified with $\ell ^{\infty }$ (the space of bounded sequences).
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Furthermore, the continuous duals of the Banach spaces c (consisting of all convergent sequences, with the supremum norm) and $c_{0}$ (the sequences converging to zero) are both naturally identified with $\ell ^{1}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] By the Riesz representation theorem, the continuous dual of a Hilbert space is again a Hilbert space which is anti-isomorphic to the original space.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] This gives rise to the bra–ket notation used by physicists in the mathematical formulation of quantum mechanics.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] By the Riesz–Markov–Kakutani representation theorem, the continuous dual of certain spaces of continuous functions can be described using measures.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] The resulting functional $T'(\varphi )$ is in $V'$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] The assignment $T\to T'$ produces a linear map between the space of continuous linear maps from V to W and the space of linear maps from $W'$ to $V'$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] When V and W are normed spaces, the norm of the transpose in $L(W',V')$ is equal to that of T in $L(V,W)$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Several properties of transposition depend upon the Hahn–Banach theorem.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] For example, the bounded linear map T has dense range if and only if the transpose $T'$ is injective.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] When T is a compact linear map between two Banach spaces V and W , then the transpose $T'$ is compact.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] This can be proved using the Arzelà–Ascoli theorem.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] When V is a Hilbert space, there is an antilinear isomorphism $i_{V}$ from V onto its continuous dual $V'$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Then, the dual of the quotient $V/W$ can be identified with $W^{\perp }$ , and the dual of W can be identified with the quotient $V'/{W^{\perp }}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Indeed, let P denote the canonical surjection from V onto the quotient $V/W$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Then the transpose $P'$ is an isometric isomorphism from $(V/W)'$ into $V'$ , with range equal to $W^{\perp }$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] If j denotes the injection map from W into V , then the kernel of the transpose $j'$ is the annihilator of W : $\ker(j')=W^{\perp }$ and it follows from the Hahn–Banach theorem that $j'$ induces an isometric isomorphism $V/W^{\perp }$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] If the dual of a normed space V is separable, then so is the space V itself.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] The converse is not true: for example, the space $l^{1}$ is separable, but its dual $\ell ^{\infty }$ is not.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] As a consequence of the Hahn–Banach theorem, this map is in fact an isometry, meaning $\|\Psi (x)\|=\|x\|$ for all $x\in V$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Normed spaces for which the map $\Psi$ is a bijection are called reflexive.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] When V is a topological vector space then $\Psi$ ( x ) can still be defined by the same formula, for every $x\in V$ , however several difficulties arise.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] First, when V is not locally convex, the continuous dual may be equal to { 0 } and the map $\Psi$ trivial.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] However, if V is Hausdorff and locally convex, the map $\Psi$ is injective from V to the algebraic dual $V^{*}$ of the continuous dual, again as a consequence of the Hahn–Banach theorem.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Second, even in the locally convex setting, several natural vector space topologies can be defined on the continuous dual $V'$ , so that the continuous double dual $V''$ is not uniquely defined as a set.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] be continuous for the chosen topology on $V'$ .
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] Further, there is still a choice of a topology on $V''$ , and continuity of $\Psi$ depends upon this choice.
[src:functional-analysis/dual-space] As a consequence, defining reflexivity in this framework is more involved than in the normed case.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] The usage of the word *functional* as a noun goes back to the calculus of variations, implying a function whose argument is a function.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] The term was first used in Hadamard's 1910 book on that subject.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] However, the general concept of a functional had previously been introduced in 1887 by the Italian mathematician and physicist Vito Volterra.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] The theory of nonlinear functionals was continued by students of Hadamard, in particular Fréchet and Lévy.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] Hadamard also founded the modern school of linear functional analysis further developed by Riesz and the group of Polish mathematicians around Stefan Banach.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] In modern introductory texts on functional analysis, the subject is seen as the study of vector spaces endowed with a topology, in particular infinite-dimensional spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] In contrast, linear algebra deals mostly with finite-dimensional spaces, and does not use topology.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] An important part of functional analysis is the extension of the theories of measure, integration, and probability to infinite-dimensional spaces, also known as **infinite dimensional analysis**.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] The basic and historically first class of spaces studied in functional analysis are complete normed vector spaces over the real or complex numbers.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] An important example is a Hilbert space, where the norm arises from an inner product.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] These spaces are of fundamental importance in many areas, including the mathematical formulation of quantum mechanics, machine learning, partial differential equations, and Fourier analysis.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] More generally, functional analysis includes the study of Fréchet spaces and other topological vector spaces not endowed with a norm.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] An important object of study in functional analysis are the continuous linear operators defined on Banach and Hilbert spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] These lead naturally to the definition of C*-algebras and other operator algebras.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] Hilbert spaces can be completely classified: there is a unique Hilbert space up to isomorphism for every cardinality of the orthonormal basis.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] Finite-dimensional Hilbert spaces are fully understood in linear algebra, and infinite-dimensional separable Hilbert spaces are isomorphic to $\ell ^{\,2}(\aleph _{0})\,$ .
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] Separability being important for applications, functional analysis of Hilbert spaces consequently mostly deals with this space.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] One of the open problems in functional analysis is to prove that every bounded linear operator on a Hilbert space has a proper invariant subspace.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] Many special cases of this invariant subspace problem have already been proven.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] General Banach spaces are more complicated than Hilbert spaces, and cannot be classified in such a simple manner as those.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] In particular, many Banach spaces lack a notion analogous to an orthonormal basis.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] Examples of Banach spaces are $L^{p}$ -spaces for any real number $p\geq 1$ .
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] If $\mu$ is the counting measure, then the integral may be replaced by a sum.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] Then it is not necessary to deal with equivalence classes, and the space is denoted $\ell ^{p}(X)$ , written more simply $\ell ^{p}$ in the case when X is the set of non-negative integers.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] In Banach spaces, a large part of the study involves the dual space: the space of all continuous linear maps from the space into its underlying field, so-called functionals.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] A Banach space can be canonically identified with a subspace of its bidual, which is the dual of its dual space.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] The corresponding map is an isometry but in general not onto.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] A general Banach space and its bidual need not even be isometrically isomorphic in any way, contrary to the finite-dimensional situation.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] This is explained in the dual space article.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] Also, the notion of derivative can be extended to arbitrary functions between Banach spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] See, for instance, the Fréchet derivative article.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] The uniform boundedness principle or Banach–Steinhaus theorem is one of the fundamental results in functional analysis.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] Together with the Hahn–Banach theorem and the open mapping theorem, it is considered one of the cornerstones of the field.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] In its basic form, it asserts that for a family of continuous linear operators (and thus bounded operators) whose domain is a Banach space, pointwise boundedness is equivalent to uniform boundedness in operator norm.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] The theorem was first published in 1927 by Stefan Banach and Hugo Steinhaus but it was also proven independently by Hans Hahn.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] There are many theorems known as the spectral theorem, but one in particular has many applications in functional analysis.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] This is the beginning of the vast research area of functional analysis called operator theory; see also the spectral measure.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] There is also an analogous spectral theorem for bounded normal operators on Hilbert spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] The only difference in the conclusion is that now f may be complex-valued.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] The Hahn–Banach theorem is a central tool in functional analysis.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] It allows the extension of bounded linear functionals defined on a subspace of some vector space to the whole space, and it also shows that there are "enough" continuous linear functionals defined on every normed vector space to make the study of the dual space "interesting".
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] The open mapping theorem, also known as the Banach–Schauder theorem (named after Stefan Banach and Juliusz Schauder), is a fundamental result which states that if a continuous linear operator between Banach spaces is surjective then it is an open map.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] The proof uses the Baire category theorem, and completeness of both X and Y is essential to the theorem.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] The statement of the theorem is no longer true if either space is just assumed to be a normed space, but is true if X and Y are taken to be Fréchet spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] Most spaces considered in functional analysis have infinite dimension.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] To show the existence of a vector space basis for such spaces may require Zorn's lemma.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] However, a somewhat different concept, the Schauder basis, is usually more relevant in functional analysis.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] Many theorems require the Hahn–Banach theorem, usually proved using the axiom of choice, although the strictly weaker Boolean prime ideal theorem suffices.
[src:functional-analysis/functional-analysis] The Baire category theorem, needed to prove many important theorems, also requires a form of axiom of choice.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The mathematical concept of a **Hilbert space** generalizes the notion of Euclidean space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] It extends the methods of Euclidean geometry and calculus from the two-dimensional Euclidean plane and three-dimensional space to spaces of any finite or infinite dimension.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] A Hilbert space is an abstract vector space, and it has the additional structure of an inner product that allows length and angle to be measured.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Finally, Hilbert spaces are required to be complete, a property that stipulates the existence of enough limits in the space to allow the techniques of calculus to be used.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Hilbert spaces were studied beginning in the first decade of the 20th century by David Hilbert (after whom they are named), Erhard Schmidt, and Frigyes Riesz.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] They are indispensable tools in the theories of partial differential equations, quantum mechanics, Fourier analysis (which includes applications to signal processing and heat transfer), and ergodic theory (which forms the mathematical underpinning of thermodynamics).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] John von Neumann coined the term *Hilbert space* for the abstract concept that underlies many of these diverse applications.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The success of Hilbert space methods ushered in a very fruitful era for functional analysis.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Apart from the classical Euclidean vector spaces, examples of Hilbert spaces include spaces of square-integrable functions, spaces of sequences, Sobolev spaces consisting of generalized functions, and Hardy spaces of holomorphic functions.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Geometric intuition plays an important role in many aspects of Hilbert space theory.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Exact analogs of the Pythagorean theorem and parallelogram law hold in a Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] At a deeper level, perpendicular projection onto a linear subspace plays a significant role in optimization problems and other aspects of the theory.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] An element of a Hilbert space can be uniquely specified by its coordinates with respect to an orthonormal basis, in analogy with Cartesian coordinates in classical geometry.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] When this basis is countably infinite, it allows identifying the Hilbert space with the space of the infinite sequences that are square-summable.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The latter space is often in the older literature referred to as *the* Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] One of the most familiar examples of a Hilbert space is the Euclidean vector space consisting of three-dimensional vectors, denoted by $\mathbf {R} ^{3}$ , and equipped with the dot product.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The dot product takes two vectors **x** and **y**, and produces a real number **x** ⋅ **y**.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] It is positive definite: for all vectors **x**, **x** ⋅ **x** ≥ 0 , with equality if and only if **x** = **0**.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] An operation on pairs of vectors that, like the dot product, satisfies these three properties is known as a (real) inner product.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] A vector space equipped with such an inner product is known as a (real) inner product space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Every finite-dimensional inner product space is also a Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Multivariable calculus in Euclidean space relies on the ability to compute limits, and to have useful criteria for concluding that limits exist.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Hilbert spaces are often taken over the complex numbers.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The real part of ⟨*z*, *w*⟩ gives the usual two-dimensional Euclidean dot product.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] A second example is the space **C**2 whose elements are pairs of complex numbers *z* = (*z*1, *z*2).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The real part of ⟨*z*, *w*⟩ is then the four-dimensional Euclidean dot product.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] A *Hilbert space* is a real or complex inner product space that is also a complete metric space with respect to the distance function induced by the inner product.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The inner product is linear in its first argument.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] A *real inner product space* is defined in the same way, except that *H* is a real vector space and the inner product takes real values.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Such an inner product will be a bilinear map and $(H,H,\langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle )$ will form a dual system.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] This last property is ultimately a consequence of the more fundamental Cauchy–Schwarz inequality, which asserts $\left|\langle x,y\rangle \right|\leq \|x\|\|y\|$ with equality if and only if x and y are linearly dependent.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] With a distance function defined in this way, any inner product space is a metric space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] An inner product space is sometimes known as a *pre-Hilbert space*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Any pre-Hilbert space that is additionally also a complete space is a Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The *completeness* of *H* is expressed using a form of the Cauchy criterion for sequences in *H*: a pre-Hilbert space *H* is complete if every Cauchy sequence converges with respect to this norm to an element in the space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] As a complete normed space, Hilbert spaces are by definition also Banach spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] As such they are topological vector spaces, in which topological notions like the openness and closedness of subsets are well defined.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Of special importance is the notion of a closed linear subspace of a Hilbert space that, with the inner product induced by restriction, is also complete (being a closed set in a complete metric space) and therefore a Hilbert space in its own right.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The sequence space ${\textstyle \ell ^{2}}$ consists of all infinite sequences **z** = (*z*1, *z*2, ...) of complex numbers such that the series $\sum _{n=1}^{\infty }|z_{n}|^{2}$ of its squared norms converges.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Completeness of the space holds provided that whenever a series of elements from ${\textstyle \ell ^{2}}$ converges absolutely (in norm), then it converges to an element of ${\textstyle \ell ^{2}}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The proof is basic in mathematical analysis, and permits mathematical series of elements of the space to be manipulated with the same ease as series of complex numbers (or vectors in a finite-dimensional Euclidean space).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Prior to the development of Hilbert spaces, other generalizations of Euclidean spaces were known to mathematicians and physicists.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Other objects studied at the turn of the 20th century, in particular spaces of sequences (including series) and spaces of functions, can naturally be thought of as linear spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Functions, for instance, can be added together or multiplied by constant scalars, and these operations obey the algebraic laws satisfied by addition and scalar multiplication of spatial vectors.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] In the first decade of the 20th century, parallel developments led to the introduction of Hilbert spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] that has many of the familiar properties of the Euclidean dot product.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] In particular, the idea of an orthogonal family of functions has meaning.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] where K is a continuous function symmetric in x and y.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] where the functions φn are orthogonal in the sense that ⟨*φ**n*, *φ**m*⟩ = 0 for all *n* ≠ *m*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The individual terms in this series are sometimes referred to as elementary product solutions.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] However, there are eigenfunction expansions that fail to converge in a suitable sense to a square-integrable function: the missing ingredient, which ensures convergence, is completeness.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The second development was the Lebesgue integral, an alternative to the Riemann integral introduced by Henri Lebesgue in 1904.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The Lebesgue integral made it possible to integrate a much broader class of functions.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] In 1907, Frigyes Riesz and Ernst Sigismund Fischer independently proved that the space *L*2 of square Lebesgue-integrable functions is a complete metric space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Further basic results were proved in the early 20th century.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] For example, the Riesz representation theorem was independently established by Maurice Fréchet and Frigyes Riesz in 1907.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] John von Neumann coined the term *abstract Hilbert space* in his work on unbounded Hermitian operators.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Although other mathematicians such as Hermann Weyl and Norbert Wiener had already studied particular Hilbert spaces in great detail, often from a physically motivated point of view, von Neumann gave the first complete and axiomatic treatment of them.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Von Neumann later used them in his seminal work on the foundations of quantum mechanics, and in his continued work with Eugene Wigner.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The name "Hilbert space" was soon adopted by others, for example by Hermann Weyl in his book on quantum mechanics and the theory of groups.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The significance of the concept of a Hilbert space was underlined with the realization that it offers one of the best mathematical formulations of quantum mechanics.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] In short, the states of a quantum mechanical system are vectors in a certain Hilbert space, the observables are hermitian operators on that space, the symmetries of the system are unitary operators, and measurements are orthogonal projections.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The relation between quantum mechanical symmetries and unitary operators provided an impetus for the development of the unitary representation theory of groups, initiated in the 1928 work of Hermann Weyl.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The algebra of observables in quantum mechanics is naturally an algebra of operators defined on a Hilbert space, according to Werner Heisenberg's matrix mechanics formulation of quantum theory.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Von Neumann began investigating operator algebras in the 1930s, as rings of operators on a Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Such algebras are now known as von Neumann algebras.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The spectral theorem for self-adjoint operators in particular that underlies much of the existing Hilbert space theory was generalized to C*-algebras.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] These techniques are now basic in abstract harmonic analysis and representation theory.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Lebesgue spaces are function spaces associated to measure spaces (*X*, *M*, *μ*), where *X* is a set, *M* is a σ-algebra of subsets of *X*, and *μ* is a countably additive measure on *M*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] where the second form (conjugation of the first element) is commonly found in the theoretical physics literature.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] For *f* and *g* in *L*2, the integral exists because of the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality, and defines an inner product on the space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Equipped with this inner product, *L*2 is in fact complete.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The Lebesgue integral is essential to ensure completeness: on domains of real numbers, for instance, not enough functions are Riemann integrable.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The Lebesgue spaces appear in many natural settings.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The spaces *L*2(**R**) and *L*2([0,1]) of square-integrable functions with respect to the Lebesgue measure on the real line and unit interval, respectively, are natural domains on which to define the Fourier transform and Fourier series.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] In other situations, the measure may be something other than the ordinary Lebesgue measure on the real line.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] For instance, if *w* is any positive measurable function, the space of all measurable functions *f* on the interval [0, 1] satisfying $\int _{0}^{1}{\bigl |}f(t){\bigr |}^{2}w(t)\,\mathrm {d} t<\infty$ is called the weighted *L*2 space *L*2 *w*([0, 1]), and *w* is called the weight function.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Weighted *L*2 spaces like this are frequently used to study orthogonal polynomials, because different families of orthogonal polynomials are orthogonal with respect to different weighting functions.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Sobolev spaces, denoted by *H**s* or *W**s*,2, are Hilbert spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] These are a special kind of function space in which differentiation may be performed, but that (unlike other Banach spaces such as the Hölder spaces) support the structure of an inner product.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Because differentiation is permitted, Sobolev spaces are a convenient setting for the theory of partial differential equations.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] They also form the basis of the theory of direct methods in the calculus of variations.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] For *s* a non-negative integer and Ω ⊂ **R***n*, the Sobolev space *H**s*(Ω) contains *L*2 functions whose weak derivatives of order up to *s* are also *L*2.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Sobolev spaces can also be defined when *s* is not an integer.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Sobolev spaces are also studied from the point of view of spectral theory, relying more specifically on the Hilbert space structure.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Here Δ is the Laplacian and (1 − Δ)−*s* / 2 is understood in terms of the spectral mapping theorem.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Apart from providing a workable definition of Sobolev spaces for non-integer *s*, this definition also has particularly desirable properties under the Fourier transform that make it ideal for the study of pseudodifferential operators.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Using these methods on a compact Riemannian manifold, one can obtain for instance the Hodge decomposition, which is the basis of Hodge theory.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The Hardy spaces are function spaces, arising in complex analysis and harmonic analysis, whose elements are certain holomorphic functions in a complex domain.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Let *U* denote the unit disc in the complex plane.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Then the Hardy space *H*2(*U*) is defined as the space of holomorphic functions *f* on *U* such that the means $M_{r}(f)={\frac {1}{2\pi }}\int _{0}^{2\pi }\left|f{\bigl (}re^{i\theta }{\bigr )}\right|^{2}\,\mathrm {d} \theta$ remain bounded for *r* < 1.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Hardy spaces in the disc are related to Fourier series.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Thus *H*2(*U*) consists of those functions that are *L*2 on the circle, and whose negative frequency Fourier coefficients vanish.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The Bergman spaces are another family of Hilbert spaces of holomorphic functions.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Clearly *L*2, *h*(*D*) is a subspace of *L*2(*D*); in fact, it is a closed subspace, and so a Hilbert space in its own right.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] This is a consequence of the estimate, valid on compact subsets *K* of *D*, that $\sup _{z\in K}\left|f(z)\right|\leq C_{K}\left\|f\right\|_{2}\,,$ which in turn follows from Cauchy's integral formula.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Thus convergence of a sequence of holomorphic functions in *L*2(*D*) implies also compact convergence, and so the limit function is also holomorphic.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Another consequence of this inequality is that the linear functional that evaluates a function *f* at a point of *D* is actually continuous on *L*2,*h*(*D*).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The Riesz representation theorem implies that the evaluation functional can be represented as an element of *L*2,*h*(*D*).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The integrand $K(\zeta ,z)={\overline {\eta _{z}(\zeta )}}$ is known as the Bergman kernel of *D*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] A Bergman space is an example of a reproducing kernel Hilbert space, which is a Hilbert space of functions along with a kernel *K*(*ζ*, *z*) that verifies a reproducing property analogous to this one.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The Hardy space *H*2(*D*) also admits a reproducing kernel, known as the Szegő kernel.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Reproducing kernels are common in other areas of mathematics as well.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] For instance, in harmonic analysis the Poisson kernel is a reproducing kernel for the Hilbert space of square-integrable harmonic functions in the unit ball.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The latter is a Hilbert space because the mean theorem for harmonic functions implies $L^{2}$ -bounded point evaluations, from which it follows that it is a closed subspace of $L^{2}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Many of the applications of Hilbert spaces exploit the fact that Hilbert spaces support generalizations of simple geometric concepts like projection and change of basis from their usual finite dimensional setting.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] In particular, the spectral theory of continuous self-adjoint linear operators on a Hilbert space generalizes the usual spectral decomposition of a matrix, and this often plays a major role in applications of the theory to other areas of mathematics and physics.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] In the theory of ordinary differential equations, spectral methods on a suitable Hilbert space are used to study the behavior of eigenvalues and eigenfunctions of differential equations.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] For example, the Sturm–Liouville problem arises in the study of the harmonics of waves in a violin string or a drum, and is a central problem in ordinary differential equations.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The problem only has solutions for certain values of *λ*, called eigenvalues of the system, and this is a consequence of the spectral theorem for compact operators applied to the integral operator defined by the Green's function for the system.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Furthermore, another consequence of this general result is that the eigenvalues *λ* of the system can be arranged in an increasing sequence tending to infinity.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Hilbert spaces form a basic tool in the study of partial differential equations.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] For many classes of partial differential equations, such as linear elliptic equations, it is possible to consider a generalized solution (known as a weak solution) by enlarging the class of functions.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Many weak formulations involve the class of Sobolev functions, which is a Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] A suitable weak formulation reduces to a geometrical problem, the analytic problem of finding a solution or, often what is more important, showing that a solution exists and is unique for given boundary data.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] For linear elliptic equations, one geometrical result that ensures unique solvability for a large class of problems is the Lax–Milgram theorem.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] This strategy forms the rudiment of the Galerkin method (a finite element method) for numerical solution of partial differential equations.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] An example is the Poisson equation −Δ*u* = *g* with Dirichlet boundary conditions in a bounded domain Ω in **R**2.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] This can be recast in terms of the Hilbert space *H*1 0(Ω) consisting of functions *u* such that *u*, along with its weak partial derivatives, are square integrable on Ω, and vanish on the boundary.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Since the Poisson equation is elliptic, it follows from Poincaré's inequality that the bilinear form *a* is coercive.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The Lax–Milgram theorem then ensures the existence and uniqueness of solutions of this equation.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Hilbert spaces allow for many elliptic partial differential equations to be formulated in a similar way, and the Lax–Milgram theorem is then a basic tool in their analysis.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] With suitable modifications, similar techniques can be applied to parabolic partial differential equations and certain hyperbolic partial differential equations.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The field of ergodic theory is the study of the long-term behavior of chaotic dynamical systems.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The laws of thermodynamics are assertions about such average behavior.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] In particular, one formulation of the zeroth law of thermodynamics asserts that over sufficiently long timescales, the only functionally independent measurement that one can make of a thermodynamic system in equilibrium is its total energy, in the form of temperature.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] An ergodic dynamical system is one for which, apart from the energy—measured by the Hamiltonian—there are no other functionally independent conserved quantities on the phase space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] More explicitly, suppose that the energy *E* is fixed, and let Ω*E* be the subset of the phase space consisting of all states of energy *E* (an energy surface), and let *T**t* denote the evolution operator on the phase space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The dynamical system is ergodic if every invariant measurable function on Ω*E* is constant almost everywhere.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] An invariant function *f* is one for which $f(T_{t}w)=f(w)$ for all *w* on Ω*E* and all time *t*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Liouville's theorem implies that there exists a measure *μ* on the energy surface that is invariant under the time translation.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] That is, the long time average of an observable *f* is equal to its expectation value over an energy surface.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] One of the basic goals of Fourier analysis is to decompose a function into a (possibly infinite) linear combination of given basis functions: the associated Fourier series.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The example of adding up the first few terms in a Fourier series for a sawtooth function is shown in the figure.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The basis functions are sine waves with wavelengths ⁠*λ*/*n*⁠ (for integer *n*) shorter than the wavelength *λ* of the sawtooth itself (except for *n* = 1, the *fundamental* wave).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] A significant problem in classical Fourier series asks in what sense the Fourier series converges, if at all, to the function *f*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Hilbert space methods provide one possible answer to this question.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The functions *en*(*θ*) = *e*2π*inθ* form an orthogonal basis of the Hilbert space *L*2([0, 1]).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Consequently, any square-integrable function can be expressed as a series $f(\theta )=\sum _{n}a_{n}e_{n}(\theta )\,,\quad a_{n}=\langle f,e_{n}\rangle$ and, moreover, this series converges in the Hilbert space sense (that is, in the *L*2 mean).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The problem can also be studied from the abstract point of view: every Hilbert space has an orthonormal basis, and every element of the Hilbert space can be written in a unique way as a sum of multiples of these basis elements.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The coefficients appearing on these basis elements are sometimes known abstractly as the Fourier coefficients of the element of the space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The abstraction is especially useful when it is more natural to use different basis functions for a space such as *L*2([0, 1]).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] In many circumstances, it is desirable not to decompose a function into trigonometric functions, but rather into orthogonal polynomials or wavelets for instance, and in higher dimensions into spherical harmonics.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The coefficients {*a**j*} are selected to make the magnitude of the difference ‖*f* − *f**n*‖2 as small as possible.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] That this formula minimizes the difference ‖*f* − *f**n*‖2 is a consequence of Bessel's inequality and Parseval's formula.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] In various applications to physical problems, a function can be decomposed into physically meaningful eigenfunctions of a differential operator (typically the Laplace operator): this forms the foundation for the spectral study of functions, in reference to the spectrum of the differential operator.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] A concrete physical application involves the problem of hearing the shape of a drum: given the fundamental modes of vibration that a drumhead is capable of producing, can one infer the shape of the drum itself?
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The mathematical formulation of this question involves the Dirichlet eigenvalues of the Laplace equation in the plane, that represent the fundamental modes of vibration in direct analogy with the integers that represent the fundamental modes of vibration of the violin string.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Spectral theory also underlies certain aspects of the Fourier transform of a function.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The Fourier transformation is also geometrical, in a sense made precise by the Plancherel theorem, that asserts that it is an isometry of one Hilbert space (the "time domain") with another (the "frequency domain").
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] In other words, the possible states are points in the projectivization of a Hilbert space, usually called the complex projective space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Each observable is represented by a self-adjoint linear operator acting on the state space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Each eigenstate of an observable corresponds to an eigenvector of the operator, and the associated eigenvalue corresponds to the value of the observable in that eigenstate.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The inner product between two state vectors is a complex number known as a probability amplitude.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] During an ideal measurement of a quantum mechanical system, the probability that a system collapses from a given initial state to a particular eigenstate is given by the square of the absolute value of the probability amplitudes between the initial and final states.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The possible results of a measurement are the eigenvalues of the operator—which explains the choice of self-adjoint operators, for all the eigenvalues must be real.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The probability distribution of an observable in a given state can be found by computing the spectral decomposition of the corresponding operator.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] For a general system, states are typically not pure, but instead are represented as statistical mixtures of pure states, or mixed states, given by density matrices: self-adjoint operators of trace one on a Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Moreover, for general quantum mechanical systems, the effects of a single measurement can influence other parts of a system in a manner that is described instead by a positive operator valued measure.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Thus the structure both of the states and observables in the general theory is considerably more complicated than the idealization for pure states.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] In probability theory, Hilbert spaces also have diverse applications.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Here a fundamental Hilbert space is the space of random variables on a given probability space, having class $L^{2}$ (finite first and second moments).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] A common operation in statistics is that of centering a random variable by subtracting its expectation.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Thus if X is a random variable, then $X-E(X)$ is its centering.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] In the Hilbert space view, this is the orthogonal projection of X onto the kernel of the expectation operator, which a continuous linear functional on the Hilbert space (in fact, the inner product with the constant random variable 1), and so this kernel is a closed subspace.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The conditional expectation has a natural interpretation in the Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Suppose that a probability space $(\Omega ,P,{\mathcal {B}})$ is given, where ${\mathcal {B}}$ is a sigma algebra on the set $\Omega$ , and P is a probability measure on the measure space $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {B}})$ .
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] If ${\mathcal {F}}\leq {\mathcal {B}}$ is a sigma subalgebra of ${\mathcal {B}}$ , then the conditional expectation $E[X\mid {\mathcal {F}}]$ is the orthogonal projection of X onto the subspace of $L^{2}(\Omega ,P)$ consisting of the ${\mathcal {F}}$ -measurable functions.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] If the random variable X in $L^{2}(\Omega ,P)$ is independent of the sigma algebra ${\mathcal {F}}$ then conditional expectation $E(X\mid {\mathcal {F}})=E(X)$ , i.e., its projection onto the ${\mathcal {F}}$ -measurable functions is constant.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Equivalently, the projection of its centering is zero.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] In particular, if two random variables X and Y (in $L^{2}(\Omega ,P)$ ) are independent, then the centered random variables $X-E(X)$ and $Y-E(Y)$ are orthogonal.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The analysis of variance could use the Pythagorean Theorem so that the variance is viewed as the decomposition of the squared length of a vector into the sum of the squared lengths of several vectors.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The theory of martingales can be formulated in Hilbert spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] A martingale in a Hilbert space is a sequence $x_{1},x_{2},\dots$ of elements of a Hilbert space such that, for each *n*, $x_{n}$ is the orthogonal projection of $x_{n+1}$ onto the linear hull of $x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] If the $x_{k}$ are random variables, this reproduces the usual definition of a (discrete) martingale: the expectation of $x_{n+1}$ , conditioned on $x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}$ , is equal to $x_{n}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Hilbert spaces are also used throughout the foundations of the Itô calculus.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] To any square-integrable martingale, it is possible to associate a Hilbert norm on the space of equivalence classes of progressively measurable processes with respect to the martingale (using the quadratic variation of the martingale as the measure).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The Itô integral can be constructed by first defining it for simple processes, and then exploiting their density in the Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] A deeper application of Hilbert spaces that is especially important in the theory of Gaussian processes is an attempt, due to Leonard Gross and others, to make sense of certain formal integrals over infinite dimensional spaces like the Feynman path integral from quantum field theory.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The problem with integrals like this is that there is no infinite dimensional Lebesgue measure.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The notion of an abstract Wiener space allows one to construct a measure on a Banach space *B* that contains a Hilbert space *H*, called the Cameron–Martin space, as a dense subset, out of a finitely additive cylinder set measure on *H*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The resulting measure on *B* is countably additive and invariant under translation by elements of *H*, and this provides a mathematically rigorous way of thinking of the Wiener measure as a Gaussian measure adapted to the Sobolev space $H^{1}([0,\infty ))$ .
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Any true physical color can be represented by a combination of pure spectral colors.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] As physical colors can be composed of any number of spectral colors, the space of physical colors may aptly be represented by a Hilbert space over spectral colors.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] Humans have three types of cone cells for color perception, so the perceivable colors can be represented by 3-dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p01] The many-to-one linear mapping from the Hilbert space of physical colors to the Euclidean space of human perceivable colors explains why many distinct physical colors may be perceived by humans to be identical (e.g., pure yellow light versus a mix of red and green light, see *Metamerism*).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Two vectors *u* and *v* in a Hilbert space *H* are orthogonal when ⟨*u*, *v*⟩ = 0.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] More generally, when *S* is a subset in *H*, the notation *u* ⊥ *S* means that *u* is orthogonal to every element from *S*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Whereas the Pythagorean identity as stated is valid in any inner product space, completeness is required for the extension of the Pythagorean identity to series.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] By definition, every Hilbert space is also a Banach space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Conversely, every Banach space in which the parallelogram identity holds is a Hilbert space, and the inner product is uniquely determined by the norm by the polarization identity.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The parallelogram law implies that any Hilbert space is a uniformly convex Banach space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This subsection employs the Hilbert projection theorem.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This is equivalent to saying that there is a point with minimal norm in the translated convex set *D* = *C* − *x*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The proof consists in showing that every minimizing sequence (*dn*) ⊂ *D* is Cauchy (using the parallelogram identity) hence converges (using completeness) to a point in *D* that has minimal norm.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] More generally, this holds in any uniformly convex Banach space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This point *y* is the *orthogonal projection* of *x* onto *F*, and the mapping *PF* : *x* → *y* is linear (see *§ Orthogonal complements and projections*).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This result is especially significant in applied mathematics, especially numerical analysis, where it forms the basis of least squares methods.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] In particular, when *F* is not equal to *H*, one can find a nonzero vector *v* orthogonal to *F* (select *x* ∉ *F* and *v* = *x* − *y*).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] A very useful criterion is obtained by applying this observation to the closed subspace *F* generated by a subset *S* of *H*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The dual space *H** is the space of all continuous linear functions from the space *H* into the base field.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] It carries a natural norm, defined by $\|\varphi \|=\sup _{\|x\|=1,x\in H}|\varphi (x)|\,.$ This norm satisfies the parallelogram law, and so the dual space is also an inner product space where this inner product can be defined in terms of this dual norm by using the polarization identity.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The dual space is also complete so it is a Hilbert space in its own right.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] If *e*• = (*e**i*)*i* ∈ *I* is a complete orthonormal basis for H then the inner product on the dual space of any two $f,g\in H^{*}$ is $\langle f,g\rangle _{H^{*}}=\sum _{i\in I}f(e_{i}){\overline {g(e_{i})}}$ where all but countably many of the terms in this series are zero.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The Riesz representation theorem affords a convenient description of the dual space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The Riesz representation theorem states that the map from *H* to *H** defined by *u* ↦ *φu* is surjective, which makes this map an isometric antilinear isomorphism.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] So to every element *φ* of the dual *H** there exists one and only one *uφ* in *H* such that $\langle x,u_{\varphi }\rangle =\varphi (x)$ for all *x* ∈ *H*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The reversal of order on the right-hand side restores linearity in *φ* from the antilinearity of *uφ*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] In the real case, the antilinear isomorphism from *H* to its dual is actually an isomorphism, and so real Hilbert spaces are naturally isomorphic to their own duals.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The representing vector *uφ* is obtained in the following way.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] When *φ* ≠ 0, the kernel *F* = Ker(*φ*) is a closed vector subspace of *H*, not equal to *H*, hence there exists a nonzero vector *v* orthogonal to *F*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The vector *u* is a suitable scalar multiple *λv* of *v*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This correspondence *φ* ↔ *u* is exploited by the bra–ket notation popular in physics.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] It is common in physics to assume that the inner product, denoted by ⟨*x*|*y*⟩, is linear on the right, $\langle x|y\rangle =\langle y,x\rangle \,.$ The result ⟨*x*|*y*⟩ can be seen as the action of the linear functional ⟨*x*| (the *bra*) on the vector |*y*⟩ (the *ket*).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The Riesz representation theorem relies fundamentally not just on the presence of an inner product, but also on the completeness of the space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] In fact, the theorem implies that the topological dual of any inner product space can be identified with its completion.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] An immediate consequence of the Riesz representation theorem is also that a Hilbert space *H* is reflexive, meaning that the natural map from *H* into its double dual space is an isomorphism.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] In a Hilbert space *H*, a sequence {*xn*} is weakly convergent to a vector *x* ∈ *H* when $\lim _{n}\langle x_{n},v\rangle =\langle x,v\rangle$ for every *v* ∈ *H*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] For example, any orthonormal sequence {*fn*} converges weakly to 0, as a consequence of Bessel's inequality.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Every weakly convergent sequence {*xn*} is bounded, by the uniform boundedness principle.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Conversely, every bounded sequence in a Hilbert space admits weakly convergent subsequences (Alaoglu's theorem).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This fact may be used to prove minimization results for continuous convex functionals, in the same way that the Bolzano–Weierstrass theorem is used for continuous functions on **R***d*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This fact (and its various generalizations) are fundamental for direct methods in the calculus of variations.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Minimization results for convex functionals are also a direct consequence of the slightly more abstract fact that closed bounded convex subsets in a Hilbert space *H* are weakly compact, since *H* is reflexive.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The existence of weakly convergent subsequences is a special case of the Eberlein–Šmulian theorem.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Any general property of Banach spaces continues to hold for Hilbert spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The open mapping theorem states that a continuous surjective linear transformation from one Banach space to another is an open mapping meaning that it sends open sets to open sets.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] A corollary is the bounded inverse theorem, that a continuous and bijective linear function from one Banach space to another is an isomorphism (that is, a continuous linear map whose inverse is also continuous).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This theorem is considerably simpler to prove in the case of Hilbert spaces than in general Banach spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The open mapping theorem is equivalent to the closed graph theorem, which asserts that a linear function from one Banach space to another is continuous if and only if its graph is a closed set.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] In the case of Hilbert spaces, this is basic in the study of unbounded operators (see *Closed operator*).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The (geometrical) Hahn–Banach theorem asserts that a closed convex set can be separated from any point outside it by means of a hyperplane of the Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This is an immediate consequence of the best approximation property: if *y* is the element of a closed convex set *F* closest to *x*, then the separating hyperplane is the plane perpendicular to the segment *xy* passing through its midpoint.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The continuous linear operators *A* : *H*1 → *H*2 from a Hilbert space *H*1 to a second Hilbert space *H*2 are *bounded* in the sense that they map bounded sets to bounded sets.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Conversely, if an operator is bounded, then it is continuous.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The sum and the composite of two bounded linear operators is again bounded and linear.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] For *y* in *H*2, the map that sends *x* ∈ *H*1 to ⟨*Ax*, *y*⟩ is linear and continuous, and according to the Riesz representation theorem can therefore be represented in the form $\left\langle x,A^{*}y\right\rangle =\langle Ax,y\rangle$ for some vector *A***y* in *H*1.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This defines another bounded linear operator *A** : *H*2 → *H*1, the adjoint of *A*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The set B(*H*) of all bounded linear operators on *H* (meaning operators *H* → *H*), together with the addition and composition operations, the norm and the adjoint operation, is a C*-algebra, which is a type of operator algebra.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] An element *A* of B(*H*) is called 'self-adjoint' or 'Hermitian' if *A** = *A*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] If *A* is Hermitian and ⟨*Ax*, *x*⟩ ≥ 0 for every *x*, then *A* is called positive, written *A* ≥ 0.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The set of self adjoint operators admits a partial order, in which *A* ≥ *B* if *A* − *B* ≥ 0.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] If *A* has the form *B***B* for some *B*, then *A* is positive; if *B* is invertible, then *A* is strictly positive.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The spectral theorem gives a precise sense in which self-adjoint operators play the role of real-valued functions: a bounded self-adjoint operator has real spectrum and can be represented, via functional calculus, by multiplication by a real-valued function.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] More generally, a normal operator is analogous to a complex-valued function.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] It decomposes into commuting self-adjoint real and imaginary parts, $A=\operatorname {Re} A+i\operatorname {Im} A={\frac {A+A^{*}}{2}}+i{\frac {A-A^{*}}{2i}}.$ Conversely, if two self-adjoint operators commute, their sum in this form is normal.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] An element *U* of B(*H*) is called unitary if *U* is invertible and its inverse is given by *U**.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This can also be expressed by requiring that *U* be onto and ⟨*Ux*, *Uy*⟩ = ⟨*x*, *y*⟩ for all *x*, *y* ∈ *H*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The unitary operators form a group under composition, which is the isometry group of *H*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] An element of B(*H*) is compact if it sends bounded sets to relatively compact sets.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Equivalently, a bounded operator *T* is compact if, for any bounded sequence {*xk*}, the sequence {*Txk*} has a convergent subsequence.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Many integral operators are compact, and define a special class of operators known as Hilbert–Schmidt operators that are important in the study of integral equations.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Fredholm operators are bounded operators that are invertible modulo compact operators.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Thus an operator T is Fredholm if there is a bounded operator $T'$ , called a parametrix, such that $TT'-I$ is compact (right-Fredholm) and $T'T-I$ is compact (left-Fredholm).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Fredholm operators are equivalently characterized as bounded operators with a finite dimensional kernel and closed range.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Fredholm operators thus correspond to invertible elements of the Calkin algebra.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Fredholm operators can be intuitively thought of as operators that are invertible modulo finite dimensional effects.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The index of a Fredholm operator *T* is defined by $\operatorname {index} T=\dim \ker T-\dim \operatorname {coker} T\,.$ The index is homotopy invariant, and plays a deep role in differential geometry via the Atiyah–Singer index theorem.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Unbounded operators arise naturally in Hilbert spaces, especially in the study of differential operators and in the mathematical formulation of quantum mechanics.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] An unbounded operator on a Hilbert space *H* is a linear map $T:D(T)\to H$ whose domain *D*(*T*) is a linear subspace of *H*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Unlike bounded operators, an unbounded operator is usually not defined on all of *H*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] If *D*(*T*) is dense in *H*, then *T* is called a densely defined operator.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The domain of an unbounded operator is part of its definition.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] In particular, the same formula may define different operators when equipped with different domains.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Operators used in analysis are often required to be closed, meaning that the graph is closed, or closable, meaning that the operator can be extended over a larger domain to an operator whose graph is closed.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] By the closed graph theorem, a closed operator defined on all of a Hilbert space is bounded; hence a genuinely unbounded closed operator must have a proper domain.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] If *T* is densely defined, its adjoint *T** is defined as follows.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] A vector *y* ∈ *H* belongs to *D*(*T**) if the map $x\mapsto \langle Tx,y\rangle ,\qquad x\in D(T),$ is bounded with respect to the Hilbert-space norm on *D*(*T*).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] In that case the Riesz representation theorem gives a unique vector *T***y* ∈ *H* such that $\langle Tx,y\rangle =\langle x,T^{*}y\rangle$ for all *x* ∈ *D*(*T*).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] A densely defined operator is called symmetric if *T* ⊂ *T**, and self-adjoint if *T* = *T**, including equality of domains.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Self-adjoint unbounded operators play the role of observables in the Hilbert-space formulation of quantum mechanics.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Equivalently, it is the closure of this differential operator initially defined on compactly supported smooth functions.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] These operators are not defined on all of *L*2(**R**): for a general square-integrable function the derivative need not exist, and the product *xf*(*x*) need not be square integrable.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Each of the *H**i* is included as a closed subspace in the direct sum of all of the *H**i*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Moreover, the *H**i* are pairwise orthogonal.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Conversely, if there is a system of closed subspaces, *V**i*, *i* ∈ *I*, in a Hilbert space *H*, that are pairwise orthogonal and whose linear span is dense in *H*, then *H* is canonically isomorphic to the direct sum of *Vi*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] In this case, *H* is called the internal direct sum of the *Vi*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] A direct sum (internal or external) is also equipped with a family of orthogonal projections *Ei* onto the *i*th direct summand *Hi*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The spectral theorem for compact self-adjoint operators on a Hilbert space *H* states that *H* splits into the orthogonal direct sum of the eigenspaces of an operator, and also gives an explicit decomposition of the operator as a sum of projections onto the eigenspaces.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The direct sum of Hilbert spaces also appears in quantum mechanics as the Fock space of a system containing a variable number of particles, where each Hilbert space in the direct sum corresponds to an additional degree of freedom for the quantum mechanical system.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] In representation theory, the Peter–Weyl theorem guarantees that any unitary representation of a compact group on a Hilbert space splits as the direct sum of finite-dimensional representations.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] If $x_{1},y_{1}\in H_{1}$ and $x_{2},y_{2}\in H_{2}$ , then one defines an inner product on the (ordinary) tensor product as follows.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This formula then extends by sesquilinearity to an inner product on $H_{1}\otimes H_{2}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The Hilbertian tensor product of $H_{1}$ and $H_{2}$ , sometimes denoted by $H_{1}\mathbin {\widehat {\otimes }} H_{2}$ , is the Hilbert space obtained by completing $H_{1}\otimes H_{2}$ for the metric associated to this inner product.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This example is typical in the following sense.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This mapping defined on simple tensors extends to a linear identification between $H_{1}\otimes H_{2}$ and the space of finite rank operators from $H_{1}^{\ast }$ to $H_{2}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This extends to a linear isometry of the Hilbertian tensor product $H_{1}\mathbin {\widehat {\otimes }} H_{2}$ with the Hilbert space $\operatorname {HS} (H_{1}^{\ast },H_{2})$ of Hilbert–Schmidt operators from $H_{1}^{\ast }$ to $H_{2}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The identification of operators with tensor product spaces generalizes to other tensor norms.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The notion of an orthonormal basis from linear algebra generalizes over to the case of Hilbert spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] *Normalization*: Every element of the family has norm 1: ‖*e**k*‖ = 1 for all *k* ∈ *B*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] *Completeness*: The linear span of the family *e**k*, *k* ∈ *B*, is dense in *H*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] A system of vectors satisfying the first two conditions basis is called an orthonormal system or an orthonormal set (or an orthonormal sequence if *B* is countable).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Such a system is always linearly independent.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Despite the name, an orthonormal basis is not, in general, a basis in the sense of linear algebra (Hamel basis).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] More precisely, an orthonormal basis is a Hamel basis if and only if the Hilbert space is a finite-dimensional vector space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This is related to the fact that the only vector orthogonal to a dense linear subspace is the zero vector, for if *S* is any orthonormal set and *v* is orthogonal to *S*, then *v* is orthogonal to the closure of the linear span of *S*, which is the whole space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] In the infinite-dimensional case, an orthonormal basis will not be a basis in the sense of linear algebra; to distinguish the two, the latter basis is also called a Hamel basis.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] That the span of the basis vectors is dense implies that every vector in the space can be written as the sum of an infinite series, and the orthogonality implies that this decomposition is unique.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This space is the infinite-dimensional generalization of the $\ell _{2}^{n}$ space of finite-dimensional vectors.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] It is usually the first example used to show that in infinite-dimensional spaces, a set that is closed and bounded is not necessarily (sequentially) compact (as is the case in all *finite* dimensional spaces).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Indeed, the set of orthonormal vectors above shows this: It is an infinite sequence of vectors in the unit ball (i.e., the ball of points with norm less than or equal one).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This set is clearly bounded and closed; yet, no subsequence of these vectors converges to anything and consequently the unit ball in $\ell _{2}$ is not compact.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Intuitively, this is because "there is always another coordinate direction" into which the next elements of the sequence can evade.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] One can generalize the space $\ell _{2}$ in many ways.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The summation over *B* is here defined by $\sum _{b\in B}\left|x(b)\right|^{2}=\sup \sum _{n=1}^{N}\left|x(b_{n})\right|^{2}$ the supremum being taken over all finite subsets of *B*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] It follows that, for this sum to be finite, every element of *l*2(*B*) has only countably many nonzero terms.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Here the sum also has only countably many nonzero terms, and is unconditionally convergent by the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Let *f*1, ..., *f**n* be a finite orthonormal system in *H*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] It follows that *x* − *y* is orthogonal to each *f**k*, hence *x* − *y* is orthogonal to *y*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Let {*f**i*}, *i* ∈ *I*, be an arbitrary orthonormal system in *H*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Applying the preceding inequality to every finite subset *J* of *I* gives Bessel's inequality: $\sum _{i\in I}{\bigl |}\langle x,f_{i}\rangle {\bigr |}^{2}\leq \|x\|^{2},\quad x\in H$ (according to the definition of the sum of an arbitrary family of non-negative real numbers).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Geometrically, Bessel's inequality implies that the orthogonal projection of *x* onto the linear subspace spanned by the *fi* has norm that does not exceed that of *x*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] In two dimensions, this is the assertion that the length of the leg of a right triangle may not exceed the length of the hypotenuse.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Bessel's inequality is a stepping stone to the stronger result called Parseval's identity, which governs the case when Bessel's inequality is actually an equality.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Even if *B* is uncountable, Bessel's inequality guarantees that the expression is well-defined and consists only of countably many nonzero terms.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This sum is called the Fourier expansion of *x*, and the individual coefficients ⟨*x*, *e**k*⟩ are the Fourier coefficients of *x*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Conversely, if {*e**k*} is an orthonormal set such that Parseval's identity holds for every *x*, then {*e**k*} is an orthonormal basis.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] As a consequence of Zorn's lemma, *every* Hilbert space admits an orthonormal basis; furthermore, any two orthonormal bases of the same space have the same cardinality, called the Hilbert dimension of the space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] For instance, since *l*2(*B*) has an orthonormal basis indexed by *B*, its Hilbert dimension is the cardinality of *B* (which may be a finite integer, or a countable or uncountable cardinal number).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The Hilbert dimension is not greater than the Hamel dimension (the usual dimension of a vector space).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The cardinal number of *B* is the Hilbert dimension of *H*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Thus every Hilbert space is isometrically isomorphic to a sequence space *l*2(*B*) for some set *B*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] By definition, a Hilbert space is separable provided it contains a dense countable subset.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Along with Zorn's lemma, this means a Hilbert space is separable if and only if it admits a countable orthonormal basis.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] All infinite-dimensional separable Hilbert spaces are therefore isometrically isomorphic to the square-summable sequence space, $\ell ^{2}.$ Separability was originally part of the definition of Hilbert space (von Neumann 1955), and it is still assumed in physical treatments.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] For instance, Dirac (1974) refers to a separable infinite-dimensional Hilbert space as "*the* Hilbert space" and describes it informally as the limit of an n -dimensional coordinate space as n tends to infinity.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Most spaces used in physics are separable, and since these are all isomorphic to each other, one often refers to any infinite-dimensional separable Hilbert space as "*the* Hilbert space" or just "Hilbert space".
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] In the Wightman formulation of relativistic quantum field theory, the state space is likewise assumed to be a separable complex Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] However, it is sometimes argued that non-separable Hilbert spaces are also important in quantum field theory, roughly because the systems in the theory possess an infinite number of degrees of freedom.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] For instance, a bosonic field can be naturally thought of as arising from a tensor-product construction whose factors represent harmonic oscillators at each point of space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] From this perspective, a non-separable full tensor product may appear naturally, although in physical applications one usually works in a distinguished separable subspace or representation on which the observables are defined.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The set *S*⊥ is a closed subspace of *H* (can be proved easily using the linearity and continuity of the inner product) and so forms itself a Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] If *V* is a closed subspace of *H*, then *V*⊥ is called the *orthogonal complement* of *V*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] In fact, every *x* ∈ *H* can then be written uniquely as *x* = *v* + *w*, with *v* ∈ *V* and *w* ∈ *V*⊥.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Therefore, *H* is the internal Hilbert direct sum of *V* and *V*⊥.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The linear operator *PV* : *H* → *H* that maps *x* to *v* is called the *orthogonal projection* onto *V*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] There is a natural one-to-one correspondence between the set of all closed subspaces of *H* and the set of all bounded self-adjoint operators *P* such that *P*2 = *P*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This provides the geometrical interpretation of *PV*(*x*): it is the best approximation to *x* by elements of *V*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Projections *PU* and *PV* are called mutually orthogonal if *P**U**P**V* = 0.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This is equivalent to *U* and *V* being orthogonal as subspaces of *H*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The sum of the two projections *P**U* and *P**V* is a projection only if *U* and *V* are orthogonal to each other, and in that case *P**U* + *P**V* = *P**U*+*V*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The composite *P**U**P**V* is generally not a projection; in fact, the composite is a projection if and only if the two projections commute, and in that case *P**U**P**V* = *P**U*∩*V*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Every closed subspace *V* of a Hilbert space is therefore the image of an operator *P* of norm one such that *P*2 = *P*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The orthogonal complement satisfies some more elementary results.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] It is a monotone function in the sense that if *U* ⊂ *V*, then *V*⊥ ⊆ *U*⊥ with equality holding if and only if *V* is contained in the closure of *U*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This result is a special case of the Hahn–Banach theorem.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The closure of a subspace can be completely characterized in terms of the orthogonal complement: if *V* is a subspace of *H*, then the closure of *V* is equal to *V*⊥⊥.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The orthogonal complement is thus a Galois connection on the partial order of subspaces of a Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Spectral theory, for self-adjoint operators in a Hilbert space, is roughly analogous to the study of symmetric matrices over the reals or self-adjoint matrices over the complex numbers.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] In the same sense, one can obtain a "diagonalization" of a self-adjoint operator as a suitable sum (actually an integral) of orthogonal projection operators.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The spectrum of an operator *T*, denoted *σ*(*T*), is the set of complex numbers *λ* such that *T* − *λ* lacks a continuous inverse.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] If *T* is bounded, then the spectrum is always a compact set in the complex plane, and lies inside the disc |*z*| ≤ ‖*T*‖.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] If *T* is self-adjoint, then the spectrum is real.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Moreover, *m* and *M* are both contained within the spectrum.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Unlike with finite matrices, not every element of the spectrum of *T* must be an eigenvalue: the linear operator *T* − *λ* may only lack an inverse because it is not surjective.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Elements of the spectrum of an operator in the general sense are known as *spectral values*.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Since spectral values need not be eigenvalues, the spectral decomposition is often more subtle than in finite dimensions.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] However, the spectral theorem of a self-adjoint operator *T* takes a particularly simple form if, in addition, *T* is assumed to be a compact operator.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This theorem is especially important for integral operators on *L*2 with square-integrable kernels, since these operators are Hilbert–Schmidt and hence compact.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The general spectral theorem for self-adjoint operators involves a kind of operator-valued Riemann–Stieltjes integral, rather than an infinite summation.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The operators *Eλ* are monotone increasing relative to the partial order defined on self-adjoint operators; the eigenvalues correspond precisely to the jump discontinuities.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The integral is understood as a Riemann–Stieltjes integral, convergent with respect to the norm on B(*H*).
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] A somewhat similar spectral decomposition holds for normal operators, although because the spectrum may now contain non-real complex numbers, the operator-valued Stieltjes measure d*Eλ* must instead be replaced by a resolution of the identity.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The resulting continuous functional calculus has applications in particular to pseudodifferential operators.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The spectral theory of *unbounded* self-adjoint operators is only marginally more difficult than for bounded operators.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] fails to be a well-defined continuous operator.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] The self-adjointness of *T* still guarantees that the spectrum is real.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Thus the essential idea of working with unbounded operators is to look instead at the resolvent *Rλ* where *λ* is nonreal.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] This is a *bounded* normal operator, which admits a spectral representation that can then be transferred to a spectral representation of *T* itself.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] Thus the essential idea of working with unbounded operators is to study the resolvent *R**λ* = (*T* − *λ*)−1 on the resolvent set, since it is a bounded operator and can be analyzed by bounded spectral theory.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] There is also a version of the spectral theorem that applies to unbounded normal operators.
[src:functional-analysis/hilbert-space-p02] In *Gravity's Rainbow* (1973), a novel by Thomas Pynchon, one of the characters is called "Sammy Hilbert-Spaess", a pun on "Hilbert Space".
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] In mathematics, an **inner product space** is a real or complex vector space endowed with an operation called an **inner product**.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] The inner product of two vectors in the space is a scalar, often denoted with angle brackets such as in $\langle a,b\rangle$ .
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Inner products allow formal definitions of intuitive geometric notions, such as lengths, angles, and orthogonality (zero inner product) of vectors.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Inner product spaces generalize Euclidean vector spaces, in which the inner product is the dot product or *scalar product* of Cartesian coordinates.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Inner product spaces of infinite dimensions are widely used in functional analysis.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Inner product spaces over the field of complex numbers are sometimes referred to as **unitary spaces**.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] The first usage of the concept of a vector space with an inner product is due to Giuseppe Peano, in 1898.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] An inner product naturally induces an associated norm, (denoted $|x|$ and $|y|$ in the picture); so, every inner product space is a normed vector space.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] If this normed space is also complete (that is, a Banach space) then the inner product space is a Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] In this article, *F* denotes a field that is either the real numbers $\mathbb {R} ,$ or the complex numbers $\mathbb {C} .$ A scalar is thus an element of *F*.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] A bar over an expression representing a scalar denotes the complex conjugate of this scalar.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] A zero vector is denoted $\mathbf {0}$ for distinguishing it from the scalar 0.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] An *inner product* space is a vector space *V* over the field *F* together with an *inner product*, that is, a map $\langle \cdot \operatorname {,} \cdot \rangle :V\times V\to F$ that satisfies the following three properties for all vectors $x,y,z\in V$ and all scalars $a,b\in F$ .
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] If the positive-definiteness condition is replaced by merely requiring that $\langle x,x\rangle \geq 0$ for all x , then one obtains the definition of *positive semi-definite Hermitian form*.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] A positive semi-definite Hermitian form $\langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle$ is an inner product if and only if for all x , if $\langle x,x\rangle =0$ then $x=\mathbf {0}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] In the following properties, which result almost immediately from the definition of an inner product, *x*, *y* and z are arbitrary vectors, and a and b are arbitrary scalars.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Over $\mathbb {R}$ , conjugate-symmetry reduces to symmetry, and sesquilinearity reduces to bilinearity.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Hence an inner product on a real vector space is a *positive-definite symmetric bilinear form*.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Several notations are used for inner products, including $\langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle$ , $\left(\cdot ,\cdot \right)$ , $\langle \cdot |\cdot \rangle$ and $\left(\cdot |\cdot \right)$ , as well as the usual dot product.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Some authors, especially in physics and matrix algebra, prefer to define inner products and sesquilinear forms with linearity in the second argument rather than the first.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Then the first argument becomes conjugate linear, rather than the second.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Bra–ket notation in quantum mechanics also uses slightly different notation, i.e. $\langle \cdot |\cdot \rangle$ , where $\langle x|y\rangle :=\left(y,x\right)$ .
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] It is a weighted-sum version of the dot product with positive weights—up to an orthogonal transformation.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] The article on Hilbert spaces has several examples of inner product spaces, wherein the metric induced by the inner product yields a complete metric space.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] This sequence is a Cauchy sequence for the norm induced by the preceding inner product, which does not converge to a *continuous* function.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] For real random variables X and $Y,$ the expected value of their product $\langle X,Y\rangle =\mathbb {E} [XY]$ is an inner product.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] In this case, $\langle X,X\rangle =0$ if and only if $\mathbb {P} [X=0]=1$ (that is, $X=0$ almost surely), where $\mathbb {P}$ denotes the probability of the event.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] This definition of expectation as inner product can be extended to random vectors as well.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] The inner product for complex square matrices of the same size is the Frobenius inner product $\langle A,B\rangle :=\operatorname {tr} \left(AB^{\dagger }\right)$ .
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Since trace and transposition are linear and the conjugation is on the second matrix, it is a sesquilinear operator.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] On an inner product space, or more generally a vector space with a nondegenerate form (hence an isomorphism $V\to V^{*}$ ), vectors can be sent to covectors (in coordinates, via transpose), so that one can take the inner product and outer product of two vectors—not simply of a vector and a covector.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Every inner product space induces a norm, called its *canonical norm*, that is defined by $\|x\|={\sqrt {\langle x,x\rangle }}.$ With this norm, every inner product space becomes a normed vector space.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] So, every general property of normed vector spaces applies to inner product spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] These two properties show that one has indeed a norm.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] The parallelogram law is a necessary and sufficient condition for a norm to be defined by an inner product.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] to be the norm defined by an inner product.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] This is not true in general for real inner product spaces, as it is a consequence of conjugate symmetry being distinct from symmetry for complex inner products.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] This may be proved by expressing the squared norms in terms of the inner products, using additivity for expanding the right-hand side of the equation.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Suppose that $\langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle$ is an inner product on V (so it is antilinear in its second argument).
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Assume for the rest of this section that V is a complex vector space.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] The map defined by $\langle x\mid y\rangle =\langle y,x\rangle$ for all $x,y\in V$ satisfies the axioms of the inner product except that it is antilinear in its *first*, rather than its second, argument.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] The last equality is similar to the formula expressing a linear functional in terms of its real part.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] These formulas show that every complex inner product is completely determined by its real part.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Moreover, this real part defines an inner product on $V,$ considered as a real vector space.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Let $V_{\mathbb {R} }$ denote V considered as a vector space over the real numbers rather than complex numbers.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] The next examples show that although real and complex inner products have many properties and results in common, they are not entirely interchangeable.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] For instance, if $\langle x,y\rangle =0$ then $\langle x,y\rangle _{\mathbb {R} }=0,$ but the next example shows that the converse is in general *not* true.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Suppose that $V=\mathbb {C}$ has the inner product $\langle x,y\rangle :=x{\overline {y}}$ mentioned above.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Then the map $A:V\to V$ defined by $Ax=ix$ is a linear map (linear for both V and $V_{\mathbb {R} }$ ) that denotes rotation by $90^{\circ }$ in the plane.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Let V be a finite dimensional inner product space of dimension $n.$ Recall that every basis of V consists of exactly n linearly independent vectors.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Using the Gram–Schmidt process we may start with an arbitrary basis and transform it into an orthonormal basis.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] That is, into a basis in which all the elements are orthogonal and have unit norm.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] This definition of orthonormal basis generalizes to the case of infinite-dimensional inner product spaces in the following way.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Then a collection $E=\left\{e_{a}\right\}_{a\in A}$ is a *basis* for V if the subspace of V generated by finite linear combinations of elements of E is dense in V (in the norm induced by the inner product).
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] The two previous theorems raise the question of whether all inner product spaces have an orthonormal basis.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] This is a non-trivial result, and is proved below.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] The following proof is taken from Halmos's *A Hilbert Space Problem Book* (see the references).
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] This theorem can be regarded as an abstract form of Fourier series, in which an arbitrary orthonormal basis plays the role of the sequence of trigonometric polynomials.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Note that the underlying index set can be taken to be any countable set (and in fact any set whatsoever, provided $\ell ^{2}$ is defined appropriately, as is explained in the article Hilbert space).
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Normality of the sequence is by design, that is, the coefficients are so chosen so that the norm comes out to 1.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Finally the fact that the sequence has a dense algebraic span, in the *inner product norm*, follows from the fact that the sequence has a dense algebraic span, this time in the space of continuous periodic functions on $[-\pi ,\pi ]$ with the uniform norm.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] This is the content of the Weierstrass theorem on the uniform density of trigonometric polynomials.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] From the point of view of inner product space theory, there is no need to distinguish between two spaces which are isometrically isomorphic.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] The spectral theorem provides a canonical form for symmetric, unitary and more generally normal operators on finite dimensional inner product spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] A generalization of the spectral theorem holds for continuous normal operators in Hilbert spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Any of the axioms of an inner product may be weakened, yielding generalized notions.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] The generalizations that are closest to inner products occur where bilinearity and conjugate symmetry are retained, but positive-definiteness is weakened.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] This construction is used in numerous contexts.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] The Gelfand–Naimark–Segal construction is a particularly important example of the use of this technique.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Another example is the representation of semi-definite kernels on arbitrary sets.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Alternatively, one may require that the pairing be a nondegenerate form, meaning that for all non-zero $x\neq 0$ there exists some y such that $\langle x,y\rangle \neq 0,$ though y need not equal x ; in other words, the induced map to the dual space $V\to V^{*}$ is injective.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] This generalization is important in differential geometry: a manifold whose tangent spaces have an inner product is a Riemannian manifold, while if this is related to nondegenerate conjugate symmetric form the manifold is a pseudo-Riemannian manifold.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Product of vectors in Minkowski space is an example of indefinite inner product, although, technically speaking, it is not an inner product according to the standard definition above.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Minkowski space has four dimensions and indices 3 and 1 (assignment of "+" and "−" to them differs depending on conventions).
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Purely algebraic statements (ones that do not use positivity) usually only rely on the nondegeneracy (the injective homomorphism $V\to V^{*}$ ) and thus hold more generally.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] The term "inner product" is opposed to outer product (tensor product), which is a slightly more general opposite.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] Simply, in coordinates, the inner product is the product of a $1\times n$ *covector* with an $n\times 1$ vector, yielding a $1\times 1$ matrix (a scalar), while the outer product is the product of an $m\times 1$ vector with a $1\times n$ covector, yielding an $m\times n$ matrix.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] The outer product is defined for different dimensions, while the inner product requires the same dimension.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] If the dimensions are the same, then the inner product is the *trace* of the outer product (trace only being properly defined for square matrices).
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] In an informal summary: "inner is horizontal times vertical and shrinks down, outer is vertical times horizontal and expands out".
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] The inner product and outer product should not be confused with the interior product and exterior product, which are instead operations on vector fields and differential forms, or more generally on the exterior algebra.
[src:functional-analysis/inner-product-space] The inner product is more correctly called a *scalar* product in this context, as the nondegenerate quadratic form in question need not be positive definite (need not be an inner product).
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] In mathematics, and more specifically in linear algebra, a **linear map** (or **linear mapping**) is a particular kind of function between vector spaces, which respects the basic operations of vector addition and scalar multiplication.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] A standard example of a linear map is an $m\times n$ matrix, which takes vectors in n -dimensions into vectors in m -dimensions in a way that is compatible with addition of vectors, and multiplication of vectors by scalars.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] A linear map is a homomorphism of vector spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Thus, a linear map $T:V\to W$ satisfies ⁠ $T(ax+by)=aTx+bTy$ ⁠, where a and b are scalars, and x and y are vectors (elements of the vector space ⁠ V ⁠).
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Linear maps can often be represented as matrices, and simple examples include rotation and reflection linear transformations.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Let V and W be vector spaces over the same field ⁠ K ⁠, such as the real or complex numbers.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Thus, a linear map is said to be *operation preserving*.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] In other words, it does not matter whether the linear map is applied before (the right sides of the above examples) or after (the left sides of the examples) the operations of addition and scalar multiplication.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Denoting the zero elements of the vector spaces V and W by ${\textstyle \mathbf {0} _{V}}$ and ${\textstyle \mathbf {0} _{W}}$ respectively, it follows that ⁠ $f(\mathbf {0} _{V})=\mathbf {0} _{W}$ ⁠.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] A linear map $V\to K$ with K viewed as a one-dimensional vector space over itself is called a linear functional.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] These statements generalize to any left-module ${\textstyle {}_{R}M}$ over a ring R without modification, and to any right-module upon reversing of the scalar multiplication.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] If a linear map is a bijection then it is called a **linear isomorphism**.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] In the case where ⁠ $V=W$ ⁠, a linear map is called a **linear endomorphism**.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Sometimes the term **linear operator** refers to this case, but the term "linear operator" can have different meanings for different conventions.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Often, a linear map is constructed by defining it on a subset of a vector space and then *extending by linearity* to the linear span of the domain.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Suppose X and Y are vector spaces and $f:S\to Y$ is a function defined on some subset ⁠ $S\subseteq X$ ⁠.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Then a *linear extension of f to $X,$* if it exists, is a linear map $F:X\to Y$ defined on X that extends f (meaning that $F(s)=f(s)$ for all ⁠ $s\in S$ ⁠) and takes its values from the codomain of ⁠ f ⁠.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] When the subset S is a vector subspace of X then a (⁠ Y ⁠-valued) linear extension of f to all of X is guaranteed to exist if (and only if) $f:S\to Y$ is a linear map.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] In particular, if f has a linear extension to $\operatorname {span} S,$ then it has a linear extension to all of ⁠ X ⁠.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] If S is linearly independent then every function $f:S\to Y$ into any vector space has a linear extension to a (linear) map $\operatorname {span} S\to Y$ (the converse is also true).
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Every (scalar-valued) linear functional f defined on a vector subspace of a real or complex vector space X has a linear extension to all of ⁠ X ⁠.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] If V and W are finite-dimensional vector spaces and a basis is defined for each vector space, then every linear map from V to W can be represented by a matrix.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] This is useful because it allows concrete calculations.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Matrices yield examples of linear maps: if A is a real $m\times n$ matrix, then $f(\mathbf {x} )=A\mathbf {x}$ describes a linear map $\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R} ^{m}$ (see Euclidean space).
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] which implies that the function *f* is entirely determined by the vectors ⁠ $f(\mathbf {v} _{1}),\ldots ,f(\mathbf {v} _{n})$ ⁠.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Thus, the function f is entirely determined by the values of ⁠ $a_{ij}$ ⁠.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] If we put these values into an $m\times n$ matrix ⁠ M ⁠, then we can conveniently use it to compute the vector output of f for any vector in ⁠ V ⁠.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] To get ⁠ M ⁠, every column j of M is a vector ${\begin{pmatrix}a_{1j}\\\vdots \\a_{mj}\end{pmatrix}}$ corresponding to $f(\mathbf {v} _{j})$ as defined above.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] To define it more clearly, for some column j that corresponds to the mapping ⁠ $f(\mathbf {v} _{j})$ ⁠, $\mathbf {M} ={\begin{pmatrix}\ \cdots &a_{1j}&\cdots \ \\&\vdots &\\&a_{mj}&\end{pmatrix}}$ where M is the matrix of ⁠ f ⁠.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] In other words, every column $j=1,\ldots ,n$ has a corresponding vector $f(\mathbf {v} _{j})$ whose coordinates $a_{1j},\cdots ,a_{mj}$ are the elements of column ⁠ j ⁠.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] A single linear map may be represented by many matrices.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] This is because the values of the elements of a matrix depend on the bases chosen.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] The equivalent method would be the "longer" method going clockwise from the same point such that ${\textstyle \left[\mathbf {v} \right]_{B'}}$ is left-multiplied with ⁠ $P^{-1}AP$ ⁠, or ⁠ $\textstyle P^{-1}AP\left[\mathbf {v} \right]_{B'}=\left[T\left(\mathbf {v} \right)\right]_{B'}$ ⁠.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] In two-dimensional space **R**2 linear maps are described by 2 × 2 matrices.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] If a linear map is only composed of rotation, reflection, and/or uniform scaling, then the linear map is a conformal linear transformation.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] The composition of linear maps is linear: if $f:V\to W$ and ${\textstyle g:W\to Z}$ are linear, then so is their composition ⁠ $g\circ f:V\to Z$ ⁠.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] It follows from this that the class of all vector spaces over a given field *K*, together with linear maps as morphisms, forms a category.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] The inverse of a linear map, when defined, is again a linear map.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] If ${\textstyle f:V\to W}$ is linear and ${\textstyle \alpha }$ is an element of the ground field ⁠ K ⁠, then the map ⁠ $\alpha f$ ⁠, defined by ⁠ $(\alpha f)(\mathbf {x} )=\alpha (f(\mathbf {x} ))$ ⁠, is also linear.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Thus the set ${\textstyle {\mathcal {L}}(V,W)}$ of linear maps from ${\textstyle V}$ to ${\textstyle W}$ itself forms a vector space over ⁠ K ⁠, sometimes denoted ⁠ $\operatorname {Hom} (V,W)$ ⁠.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Furthermore, in the case that ⁠ $V=W$ ⁠, this vector space, denoted ⁠ $\operatorname {End} (V)$ ⁠, is an associative algebra under composition of maps, since the composition of two linear maps is again a linear map, and the composition of maps is always associative.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] This case is discussed in more detail below.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] The multiplicative identity element of this algebra is the identity map ⁠ $\operatorname {id} :V\to V$ ⁠.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] An endomorphism of ${\textstyle V}$ that is also an isomorphism is called an automorphism of ⁠ V ⁠.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] The composition of two automorphisms is again an automorphism, and the set of all automorphisms of ${\textstyle V}$ forms a group, the automorphism group of ${\textstyle V}$ which is denoted by ${\textstyle \operatorname {Aut} (V)}$ or ⁠ $\operatorname {GL} (V)$ ⁠.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Since the automorphisms are precisely those endomorphisms which possess inverses under composition, ${\textstyle \operatorname {Aut} (V)}$ is the group of units in the ring ⁠ $\operatorname {End} (V)$ ⁠.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] If ${\textstyle V}$ has finite dimension ⁠ n ⁠, then ${\textstyle \operatorname {End} (V)}$ is isomorphic to the associative algebra of all ${\textstyle n\times n}$ matrices with entries in ⁠ K ⁠.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] The automorphism group of ${\textstyle V}$ is isomorphic to the general linear group ${\textstyle \operatorname {GL} (n,K)}$ of all ${\textstyle n\times n}$ invertible matrices with entries in ⁠ K ⁠.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] ${\textstyle \ker(f)}$ is a subspace of ${\textstyle V}$ and ${\textstyle \operatorname {im} (f)}$ is a subspace of ⁠ W ⁠.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] If ${\textstyle V}$ and ${\textstyle W}$ are finite-dimensional, bases have been chosen and ${\textstyle f}$ is represented by the matrix ⁠ A ⁠, then the rank and nullity of ${\textstyle f}$ are equal to the rank and nullity of the matrix ⁠ A ⁠, respectively.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] The dimension of the co-kernel and the dimension of the image (the rank) add up to the dimension of the target space.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] For finite dimensions, this means that the dimension of the quotient space *W* / *f*(*V*) is the dimension of the target space minus the dimension of the image.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Then for an equation *f*(*x*, *y*) = (*a*, *b*) to have a solution, we must have *a* = 0 (one constraint), and in that case the solution space is (*x*, *b*) or equivalently stated, (0, *b*) + (*x*, 0), (one degree of freedom).
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] The kernel may be expressed as the subspace (*x*, 0) < *V*: the value of *x* is the freedom in a solution – while the cokernel may be expressed via the map *W* → **R**, ⁠ $(a,b)\mapsto (a)$ ⁠: given a vector (*a*, *b*), the value of *a* is the *obstruction* to there being a solution.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] An example illustrating the infinite-dimensional case is afforded by the map *f* : **R**∞ → **R**∞, ${\textstyle \left\{a_{n}\right\}\mapsto \left\{b_{n}\right\}}$ with *b*1 = 0 and *b**n* + 1 = *an* for *n* > 0.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Its image consists of all sequences with first element 0, and thus its cokernel consists of the classes of sequences with identical first element.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Thus, whereas its kernel has dimension 0 (it maps only the zero sequence to the zero sequence), its co-kernel has dimension 1.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Its image is the entire target space, and hence its co-kernel has dimension 0, but since it maps all sequences in which only the first element is non-zero to the zero sequence, its kernel has dimension 1.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] For a linear operator with finite-dimensional kernel and co-kernel, one may define *index* as: $\operatorname {ind} (f):=\dim(\ker(f))-\dim(\operatorname {coker} (f)),$ namely the degrees of freedom minus the number of constraints.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] For a transformation between finite-dimensional vector spaces, this is just the difference dim(*V*) − dim(*W*), by rank–nullity.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] This gives an indication of how many solutions or how many constraints one has: if mapping from a larger space to a smaller one, the map may be onto, and thus will have degrees of freedom even without constraints.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Conversely, if mapping from a smaller space to a larger one, the map cannot be onto, and thus one will have constraints even without degrees of freedom.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] The index of an operator is precisely the Euler characteristic of the 2-term complex 0 → *V* → *W* → 0.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] In operator theory, the index of Fredholm operators is an object of study, with a major result being the Atiyah–Singer index theorem.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] No classification of linear maps could be exhaustive.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] The following incomplete list enumerates some important classifications that do not require any additional structure on the vector space.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Let V and W denote vector spaces over a field F and let *T* : *V* → *W* be a linear map.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] T is monic or left-cancellable, which is to say, for any vector space U and any pair of linear maps *R*: *U* → *V* and *S* : *U* → *V*, the equation *TR* = *TS* implies *R* = *S*.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] T is left-invertible, which is to say there exists a linear map *S* : *W* → *V* such that *ST* is the identity map on V.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] T is epic or right-cancellable, which is to say, for any vector space U and any pair of linear maps *R* : *W* → *U* and *S* : *W* → *U*, the equation *RT* = *ST* implies *R* = *S*.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] T is right-invertible, which is to say there exists a linear map *S* : *W* → *V* such that *TS* is the identity map on W.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] T is said to be an *isomorphism* if it is both left- and right-invertible.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] This is equivalent to T being both one-to-one and onto (a bijection of sets) or also to T being both epic and monic, and so being a bimorphism.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Given a linear map which is an endomorphism whose matrix is *A*, in the basis *B* of the space it transforms vector coordinates [*u*] as [*v*] = *A*[*u*].
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] As vectors change with the inverse of *B* (vectors coordinates are contravariant) its inverse transformation is [*v*] = *B*[*v*′].
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Therefore, the matrix in the new basis is *A*′ = *B*−1*AB*, being *B* the matrix of the given basis.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Therefore, linear maps are said to be 1-co- 1-contra-variant objects, or type (1, 1) tensors.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] A *linear transformation* between topological vector spaces, for example normed spaces, may be continuous.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] If its domain and codomain are the same, it will then be a continuous linear operator.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] A linear operator on a normed linear space is continuous if and only if it is bounded, for example, when the domain is finite-dimensional.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] An infinite-dimensional domain may have discontinuous linear operators.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] An example of an unbounded, hence discontinuous, linear transformation is differentiation on the space of smooth functions equipped with the supremum norm (a function with small values can have a derivative with large values, while the derivative of 0 is 0).
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] For a specific example, sin(*nx*)/*n* converges to 0, but its derivative cos(*nx*) does not, so differentiation is not continuous at 0 (and by a variation of this argument, it is not continuous anywhere).
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] A specific application of linear maps is for geometric transformations, such as those performed in computer graphics, where the translation, rotation and scaling of 2D or 3D objects is performed by the use of a transformation matrix.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Linear mappings also are used as a mechanism for describing change: for example in calculus correspond to derivatives; or in relativity, used as a device to keep track of the local transformations of reference frames.
[src:functional-analysis/linear-operator] Another application of these transformations is in compiler optimizations of nested-loop code, and in parallelizing compiler techniques.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] In mathematics, a **normed vector space** or **normed space** is a vector space, typically over the real or complex numbers, on which a norm is defined.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] A norm is a generalization of the intuitive notion of "length" in the physical world.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] Positive definiteness: for every $x\in V$ , $\;\lVert x\rVert =0$ if and only if x is the zero vector.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] If V is a real or complex vector space as above, and $\lVert \cdot \rVert$ is a norm on V , then the ordered pair $(V,\lVert \cdot \rVert )$ is called a normed vector space.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] If it is clear from context which norm is intended, then it is common to denote the normed vector space simply by V .
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] A norm induces a distance, called its *(norm) induced metric*, by the formula $d(x,y)=\|y-x\|.$ which makes any normed vector space into a metric space and a topological vector space.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] If this metric space is complete then the normed space is a *Banach space*.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] Every normed vector space can be "uniquely extended" to a Banach space, which makes normed spaces intimately related to Banach spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] Every Banach space is a normed space but the converse is not true.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] For example, the set of the finite sequences of real numbers can be normed with the Euclidean norm, but it is not complete for this norm.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] An inner product space is a normed vector space whose norm is the square root of the inner product of a vector and itself.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] The study of normed spaces and Banach spaces is a fundamental part of functional analysis, a major subfield of mathematics.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] A **normed vector space** is a vector space equipped with a norm.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] A **seminormed vector space** is a vector space equipped with a seminorm.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] This also shows that a vector norm is a (uniformly) continuous function.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] Property 3 depends on a choice of norm $|\alpha |$ on the field of scalars.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] When the scalar field is $\mathbb {R}$ (or more generally a subset of $\mathbb {C}$ ), this is usually taken to be the ordinary absolute value, but other choices are possible.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] For example, for a vector space over $\mathbb {Q}$ one could take $|\alpha |$ to be the p -adic absolute value.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] The scalar multiplication $\,\cdot \,:\mathbb {K} \times V\to V,$ where $\mathbb {K}$ is the underlying scalar field of $V,$ is jointly continuous.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] This follows from the triangle inequality and homogeneity of the norm.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] To put it more abstractly every seminormed vector space is a topological vector space and thus carries a topological structure which is induced by the semi-norm.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] Of special interest are complete normed spaces, which are known as *Banach spaces*.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] Two norms on the same vector space are called *equivalent* if they define the same topology.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] On a finite-dimensional vector space (but not infinite-dimensional vector spaces), all norms are equivalent (although the resulting metric spaces need not be the same) And since any Euclidean space is complete, we can thus conclude that all finite-dimensional normed vector spaces are Banach spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] A normed vector space V is locally compact if and only if the unit ball $B=\{x:\|x\|\leq 1\}$ is compact, which is the case if and only if V is finite-dimensional; this is a consequence of Riesz's lemma.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] (In fact, a more general result is true: a topological vector space is locally compact if and only if it is finite-dimensional.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] The topology of a seminormed vector space has many nice properties.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] Moreover, there exists a neighbourhood basis for the origin consisting of absorbing and convex sets.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] As this property is very useful in functional analysis, generalizations of normed vector spaces with this property are studied under the name locally convex spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] A product of a family of normable spaces is normable if and only if only finitely many of the spaces are non-trivial (that is, $\neq \{0\}$ ).
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] Furthermore, X is finite-dimensional if and only if $X_{\sigma }^{\prime }$ is normable (here $X_{\sigma }^{\prime }$ denotes $X^{\prime }$ endowed with the weak-* topology).
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] Even if a metrizable topological vector space has a topology that is defined by a family of norms, then it may nevertheless still fail to be normable space (meaning that its topology can not be defined by any *single* norm).
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] The most important maps between two normed vector spaces are the continuous linear maps.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] Together with these maps, normed vector spaces form a category.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] The norm is a continuous function on its vector space.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] All linear maps between finite-dimensional vector spaces are also continuous.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] An *isometry* between two normed vector spaces is a linear map f which preserves the norm (meaning $\|f(\mathbf {v} )\|=\|\mathbf {v} \|$ for all vectors $\mathbf {v}$ ).
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] Isometries are always continuous and injective.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] A surjective isometry between the normed vector spaces V and W is called an *isometric isomorphism*, and V and W are called *isometrically isomorphic*.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] Isometrically isomorphic normed vector spaces are identical for all practical purposes.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] When speaking of normed vector spaces, we augment the notion of dual space to take the norm into account.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] The dual $V^{\prime }$ of a normed vector space V is the space of all *continuous* linear maps from V to the base field (the complexes or the reals) — such linear maps are called "functionals".
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] The norm of a functional $\varphi$ is defined as the supremum of $|\varphi (\mathbf {v} )|$ where $\mathbf {v}$ ranges over all unit vectors (that is, vectors of norm 1 ) in $V.$ This turns $V^{\prime }$ into a normed vector space.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] An important theorem about continuous linear functionals on normed vector spaces is the Hahn–Banach theorem.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] The definition of many normed spaces (in particular, Banach spaces) involves a seminorm defined on a vector space and then the normed space is defined as the quotient space by the subspace of elements of seminorm zero.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] For instance, with the $L^{p}$ spaces, the function defined by $\|f\|_{p}=\left(\int |f(x)|^{p}\;dx\right)^{1/p}$ is a seminorm on the vector space of all functions on which the Lebesgue integral on the right hand side is defined and finite.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] However, the seminorm is equal to zero for any function supported on a set of Lebesgue measure zero.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] These functions form a subspace which we "quotient out", making them equivalent to the zero function.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] Define a new function $q:X\to \mathbb {R}$ by $q\left(x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}\right):=\sum _{i=1}^{n}q_{i}\left(x_{i}\right),$ which is a seminorm on $X.$ The function q is a norm if and only if all $q_{i}$ are norms.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] For each p this defines the same topological space.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] A straightforward argument involving elementary linear algebra shows that the only finite-dimensional seminormed spaces are those arising as the product space of a normed space and a space with trivial seminorm.
[src:functional-analysis/normed-vector-space] Consequently, many of the more interesting examples and applications of seminormed spaces occur for infinite-dimensional vector spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] In linear algebra and functional analysis, a **spectral theorem** is a result about when a linear operator or matrix can be diagonalized (that is, represented as a diagonal matrix in some basis).
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] This is extremely useful because computations involving a diagonalizable matrix can often be reduced to much simpler computations involving the corresponding diagonal matrix of eigenvalues.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] The concept of diagonalization is relatively straightforward for operators on finite-dimensional vector spaces but requires some modification for operators on infinite-dimensional spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] In general, the spectral theorem identifies a class of linear operators that can be modeled by multiplication operators, which are as simple as one can hope to find.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] In more abstract language, the spectral theorem is a statement about commutative C*-algebras.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] See also spectral theory for a historical perspective.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Examples of operators to which the spectral theorem applies are self-adjoint operators or more generally normal operators on Hilbert spaces.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] The spectral theorem also provides a canonical decomposition, called the **spectral decomposition**, of the underlying vector space on which the operator acts.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Augustin-Louis Cauchy proved the spectral theorem for symmetric matrices, i.e., that every real, symmetric matrix is diagonalizable.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] In addition, Cauchy was the first to be systematic about determinants.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] The spectral theorem as generalized by John von Neumann is today perhaps the most important result of operator theory.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] This article mainly focuses on the simplest kind of spectral theorem, that for a self-adjoint operator on a Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] However, as noted above, the spectral theorem also holds for normal operators on a Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] We begin by considering a Hermitian matrix on $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ (but the following discussion will be adaptable to the more restrictive case of symmetric matrices on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ).
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] We consider a Hermitian map *A* on a finite-dimensional complex inner product space *V* endowed with a positive definite sesquilinear inner product $\langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle$ .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] An equivalent condition is that *A** = *A*, where *A** is the Hermitian conjugate of *A*.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] In the case that *A* is identified with a Hermitian matrix, the matrix of *A** is equal to its conjugate transpose.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] This condition implies that all eigenvalues of a Hermitian map are real: To see this, it is enough to apply it to the case when *x* = *y* is an eigenvector.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] (Recall that an eigenvector of a linear map *A* is a non-zero vector *v* such that *Av* = *λv* for some scalar *λ*.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] The value *λ* is the corresponding eigenvalue.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] We provide a sketch of a proof for the case where the underlying field of scalars is the complex numbers.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] By the fundamental theorem of algebra, applied to the characteristic polynomial of *A*, there is at least one complex eigenvalue *λ*1 and corresponding eigenvector *v*1, which must by definition be non-zero.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] By Hermiticity, ${\mathcal {K}}^{n-1}$ is an invariant subspace of *A*.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] To satisfy invariance, we need to check if $A(k)\in {\mathcal {K}}^{n-1}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Applying the same argument to ${\mathcal {K}}^{n-1}$ shows that *A* has at least one real eigenvalue $\lambda _{2}$ and corresponding eigenvector $v_{2}\in {\mathcal {K}}^{n-1}\perp v_{1}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Finite induction then finishes the proof.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] The matrix representation of *A* in a basis of eigenvectors is diagonal, and by the construction the proof gives a basis of mutually orthogonal eigenvectors; by choosing them to be unit vectors one obtains an orthonormal basis of eigenvectors.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] *A* can be written as a linear combination of pairwise orthogonal projections, called its **spectral decomposition**.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Let $V_{\lambda }=\{v\in V:Av=\lambda v\}$ be the eigenspace corresponding to an eigenvalue $\lambda$ .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Note that the definition does not depend on any choice of specific eigenvectors.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] In general, *V* is the orthogonal direct sum of the spaces $V_{\lambda }$ where the $\lambda$ ranges over the spectrum of A .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] When the matrix being decomposed is Hermitian, the spectral decomposition is a special case of the Schur decomposition (see the proof in case of normal matrices below).
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] The diagonal entries of $\Sigma$ are uniquely determined by A and are known as the singular values of A .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] The spectral theorem extends to a more general class of matrices.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Let *A* be an operator on a finite-dimensional inner product space.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] *A* is said to be normal if *A***A* = *AA**.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] One can show that *A* is normal if and only if it is unitarily diagonalizable using the Schur decomposition.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] That is, any matrix can be written as *A* = *UTU**, where *U* is unitary and *T* is upper triangular.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] If *A* is normal, then one sees that *TT** = *T***T*.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Therefore, *T* must be diagonal since a normal upper triangular matrix is diagonal (see normal matrix).
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] In other words, *A* is normal if and only if there exists a unitary matrix *U* such that $A=UDU^{*},$ where *D* is a diagonal matrix.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Then, the entries of the diagonal of *D* are the eigenvalues of *A*.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] The column vectors of *U* are the eigenvectors of *A* and they are orthonormal.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Unlike the Hermitian case, the entries of *D* need not be real.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] In the more general setting of Hilbert spaces, which may have an infinite dimension, the statement of the spectral theorem for compact self-adjoint operators is virtually the same as in the finite-dimensional case.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] As for Hermitian matrices, the key point is to prove the existence of at least one nonzero eigenvector.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] One cannot rely on determinants to show existence of eigenvalues, but one can use a maximization argument analogous to the variational characterization of eigenvalues.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] If the compactness assumption is removed, then it is *not* true that every self-adjoint operator has eigenvectors; see #Possible absence of eigenvectors.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] The next generalization we consider is that of bounded self-adjoint operators on a Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] This operator does not have any eigenvectors *in* $L^{2}([0,1])$ .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] However, its spectrum, suitably defined, is still equal to $[0,1]$ , see spectrum of bounded operator.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] It does also have eigenvectors in a larger space.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Namely the distribution $f(t)=\delta (t-t_{0})$ , where $\delta$ is the Dirac delta function, is an eigenvector when construed in an appropriate sense.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] The Dirac delta function is however not a function in the classical sense and does not lie in the Hilbert space *L*2[0, 1].
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Thus, the delta-functions are "generalized eigenvectors" of A but not eigenvectors in the usual sense.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] In the absence of (true) eigenvectors, one can look for a "spectral subspace" consisting of an *almost eigenvector*, i.e., a closed subspace $V_{E}$ of V associated with a Borel set $E\subset \sigma (A)$ in the spectrum of A .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] This subspace can be thought of as the closed span of generalized eigenvectors for A with eigen*values* in E .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] In the above example, where $[Af](t)=tf(t),\;$ we might consider the subspace of functions supported on a small interval $[a,a+\varepsilon ]$ inside $[0,1]$ .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] This space is invariant under A and for any f in this subspace, $Af$ is very close to $af$ .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Each subspace, in turn, is encoded by the associated projection operator, and the collection of all the subspaces is then represented by a projection-valued measure.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] An alternative formulation of the spectral theorem says that every bounded self-adjoint operator is unitarily equivalent to a multiplication operator, a relatively simple type of operator.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Multiplication operators are a direct generalization of diagonal matrices.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] A finite-dimensional Hermitian vector space V may be coordinatized as the space of functions $f:B\to \mathbb {C}$ from a basis B to the complex numbers, so that the B -coordinates of a vector are the values of the corresponding function f .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Also A is unitarily equivalent to the multiplication operator $[Tf](v)=\lambda (v)f(v)$ , where $\lambda (v)$ is the eigenvalue of $v\in B$ : that is, A multiplies each B -coordinate by the corresponding eigenvalue $\lambda (v)$ , the action of a diagonal matrix.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Finally, the operator norm $|A|=|T|$ is equal to the magnitude of the largest eigenvalue $|\lambda |_{\infty }$ .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] The spectral theorem is the beginning of the vast research area of functional analysis called operator theory; see also spectral measure.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] The only difference in the conclusion is that now *$\lambda$* may be complex-valued.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] There is also a formulation of the spectral theorem in terms of direct integrals.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] It is similar to the multiplication-operator formulation, but more canonical.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Let A be a bounded self-adjoint operator and let $\sigma (A)$ be the spectrum of A .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] The direct-integral formulation of the spectral theorem associates two quantities to A .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] The spaces $H_{\lambda }$ can be thought of as something like "eigenspaces" for A .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Note, however, that unless the one-element set $\lambda$ has positive measure, the space $H_{\lambda }$ is not actually a subspace of the direct integral.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Thus, the $H_{\lambda }$ 's should be thought of as "generalized eigenspace"—that is, the elements of $H_{\lambda }$ are "eigenvectors" that do not actually belong to the Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Although both the multiplication-operator and direct integral formulations of the spectral theorem express a self-adjoint operator as unitarily equivalent to a multiplication operator, the direct integral approach is more canonical.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] First, the set over which the direct integral takes place (the spectrum of the operator) is canonical.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Second, the function we are multiplying by is canonical in the direct-integral approach: Simply the function $\lambda \mapsto \lambda$ .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] A vector $\varphi$ is called a cyclic vector for A if the vectors $\varphi ,A\varphi ,A^{2}\varphi ,\ldots$ span a dense subspace of the Hilbert space.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Suppose A is a bounded self-adjoint operator for which a cyclic vector exists.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] In that case, there is no distinction between the direct-integral and multiplication-operator formulations of the spectral theorem.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Indeed, in that case, there is a measure $\mu$ on the spectrum $\sigma (A)$ of A such that A is unitarily equivalent to the "multiplication by $\lambda$ " operator on $L^{2}(\sigma (A),\mu )$ .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] This result represents A simultaneously as a multiplication operator *and* as a direct integral, since $L^{2}(\sigma (A),\mu )$ is just a direct integral in which each Hilbert space $H_{\lambda }$ is just $\mathbb {C}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Not every bounded self-adjoint operator admits a cyclic vector; indeed, by the uniqueness in the direct integral decomposition, this can occur only when all the $H_{\lambda }$ 's have dimension one.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] When this happens, we say that A has "simple spectrum" in the sense of spectral multiplicity theory.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] That is, a bounded self-adjoint operator that admits a cyclic vector should be thought of as the infinite-dimensional generalization of a self-adjoint matrix with distinct eigenvalues (i.e., each eigenvalue has multiplicity one).
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Although not every A admits a cyclic vector, it is easy to see that we can decompose the Hilbert space as a direct sum of invariant subspaces on which A has a cyclic vector.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] This observation is the key to the proofs of the multiplication-operator and direct-integral forms of the spectral theorem.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] One important application of the spectral theorem (in whatever form) is the idea of defining a functional calculus.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] That is, given a function f defined on the spectrum of A , we wish to define an operator $f(A)$ .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] If f is simply a positive power, $f(x)=x^{n}$ , then $f(A)$ is just the n -th power of A , $A^{n}$ .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] The interesting cases are where f is a nonpolynomial function such as a square root or an exponential.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Either of the versions of the spectral theorem provides such a functional calculus.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Many important linear operators which occur in analysis, such as differential operators, are unbounded.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] There is also a spectral theorem for self-adjoint operators that applies in these cases.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] To give an example, every constant-coefficient differential operator is unitarily equivalent to a multiplication operator.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Indeed, the unitary operator that implements this equivalence is the Fourier transform; the multiplication operator is a type of Fourier multiplier.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] In general, spectral theorem for self-adjoint operators may take several equivalent forms.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Specifically, the only reason the multiplication operator A on $L^{2}([0,1])$ is bounded, is due to the choice of domain $[0,1]$ .
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] The same operator on, e.g., $L^{2}(\mathbb {R} )$ would be unbounded.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] The notion of "generalized eigenvectors" naturally extends to unbounded self-adjoint operators, as they are characterized as non-normalizable eigenvectors.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Contrary to the case of almost eigenvectors, however, the eigenvalues can be real or complex and, even if they are real, do not necessarily belong to the spectrum.
[src:functional-analysis/spectral-theorem] Though, for self-adjoint operators there always exist a real subset of "generalized eigenvalues" such that the corresponding set of eigenvectors is complete.
